{"title_page": "Lauren Tewes", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image              = Lauren Tewes.jpg\n| caption            = Tewes in ''The Love Boat'', 1977\n| name               = Lauren Tewes\n| birth_place        = [[Braddock, Allegheny County, Pennsylvania|Braddock, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1953|10|26}}\n| known_for          = Julie McCoy \u2013 ''[[The Love Boat]]''\n| education          = [[Rio Hondo College]]<br>[[University of California, Riverside]] (withdrawn)\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| othername           = \n| occupation          = Actress \n| yearsactive        = 1976\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|John Wassel<br>|1977|1982|end=divorced}}<br>Paolo Nonnis<br>({{abbr|m.|married}} 1985; {{abbr|div.|divorced}} 1995)<br>{{marriage|Robert Nadir<br>|1996|2002|end=died}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Love boat cast 1977.JPG|thumb|upright|Tewes with fellow ''Love Boat'' cast members]]\n\n'''Cynthia Lauren Tewes''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|w|i\u02d0|z}}; born October 26, 1953) is an [[Americans|American]] actress. She is best known for her role as Julie McCoy on the [[television comedy]] [[anthology series]] ''[[The Love Boat]]'', which originally aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] from 1977\u201386.\n\n==Early years==\nTewes was born in [[Braddock, Allegheny County, Pennsylvania|Braddock, Pennsylvania]], of German extraction and one of 4 children, to Joanne (n\u00e9e Woods) and Joseph Robert Tewes, a wood pattern maker.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rZ4UuQ5N_SEC&q=%22daughter+of+Joseph+(a+wood+pattern+maker)+and+Joanne+(Woods)+Tewes.%22&dq=%22daughter+of+Joseph+(a+wood+pattern+maker)+and+Joanne+(Woods)+Tewes.%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=sbxaVca1N4iwsAS9xYGQCg&ved=0CBMQ6AEwAA|title=Contemporary Theatre, Film and Television|first=Monica M.|last=O'Donnell|date=8 March 1984|publisher=Gale|via=Google Books}}</ref>  Her early childhood was spent in industrial [[Trafford, Pennsylvania|Trafford]], near Pittsburgh before the family moved to [[Whittier, California]] when she was 8. \n\nTewes attended Ada S. Nelson Elementary School<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=24 March 1978|title=Lauren Tewes|url=|journal=Cumberland Evening Times|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> and [[Pioneer High School (Whittier, California)|Pioneer High School]] where she studied Drama, winning Best Actress award for 3 years.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dangaard|first=Colin|date=23 March 1982|title=Lauren Tewes Cooking up a Storm|url=https://gleaner.newspaperarchive.com/kingston-gleaner/1982-03-23/page-4/|journal=Kingston Gleaner|volume=|pages=4|via=}}</ref> Tewes enrolled on an [[Associate degree|associate of arts]] degree at [[Rio Hondo College]], deciding to major in Theatre Arts.  At college, she won \"The Chancellor's Award for Excellence in Theatre\", a one-year scholarship which enabled her to transfer to the [[University of California, Riverside]] as a sophomore.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://traffordhistory.org/lookingback/index.php/world-war-i-veterans/91-family-life/112-tewes|title=Lauren Tewes -- Hollywood Success|last=|first=|date=Jun 24, 1979|work=The Morning News|access-date=}}</ref>  \n\nIn 1973, when her scholarship expired, Tewes withdrew from university and joined the [[Pacific Conservatory of the Performing Arts|Pacific Conservatory Theatre]] in Santa Maria, California as an apprentice making her stage debut in ''[[Arsenic and Old Lace (play)|Arsenic and Old Lace]]'' and ''[[The Most Happy Fella]]'' before becoming a member of the Birdcage Theatre Company at [[Knott's Berry Farm]], an amusement complex outside Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://traffordhistory.org/lookingback/index.php/world-war-i-veterans/91-family-life/112-tewes|title=She Won't Rock The \"Love Boat\" - ABC's Hit Series Serenely Sails On|last=Peterson|first=Bettelou|date=Aug 19, 1979|work=Detroit Free Press|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nTewe's first break came in mid-1974 when she starred in a [[Lipton Ice Tea]] commercial, allowing her to join the [[Screen Actors Guild]] and register with an agent with the prospect to work on film projects.  \n\nIn 1975, whilst waitressing in Sunset Boulevard coffee shops and penniless, she suffered a traumatic loss when her mother was diagnosed with terminal cancer and died a year later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title='Love Boat's' Star's Hearbreaking Memory: Her Mom's Last Christmas|last=Troll|first=Harriett|date=8 September 1981|work=Weekly World News|access-date=}}</ref>    \n\nTewes obtained minor parts in TV series ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'' and ''[[Family (1976 TV series)|Family]]'' (\"Mirror, Mirror on the Wall...\") as Jill Redfield, a disenchanted Pasadena debutante. However, it was her role in ''[[Starsky and Hutch]]'' (\"Starsky and Hutch are guilty\") as Sharon Freemont, an assistant attorney which brought her to the attention of [[Aaron Spelling]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Will The Real \"Julie\" Please Stand Up?|last=|first=|date=|work=Cruise Travel; September/October 1980|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nTewes was cast for the role of cruise director Julie McCoy on ''[[The Love Boat]],'' selected from more than 100 actresses who auditioned.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-RsNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=k2YDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4543,4421645&dq=lauren+tewes+cocaine|title=Cocaine Abuse Threw Tewes' Performance Overboard|last=UPI|date=March 12, 1985|publisher=St. Petersburg Times|accessdate=2009-01-08}}</ref> She starred in the third and final pilot of the show, cast the day before production began on the [[RMS Queen Mary|RMS ''Queen Mary'']] in San Pedro.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19820219&id=soQsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wc0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2167,3714630|title=Lauren Tewes To Cruise For Two More Years|last=AP|date=February 19, 1982|publisher=Spartanburg Herald-Journal}}</ref> Tewes recalls the pilot episode:\n\n\"I had to borrow money to get a new tire, because my \u201962 Volkswagen Bug was not going to get to San Pedro\u2026. That first day, standing there in the little outfit, and I had to say, \u201dHi, welcome aboard, I\u2019m Julie McCoy, your cruise director\u201d a gazillion times. But I kept screwing it up and saying, \u201dHi, welcome aboard, I\u2019m Julie MacLeod\u2026\u201d because I was talking to Gavin MacLeod and I was so excited.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2007/10/07/love-boat-cast-and-crew-tell-all/|title='Love Boat': Cast and crew tell all|last=Snierson|first=Dan|date=7 October 2007|website=Entertainment}}</ref>   \n\nIn parallel, Tewes appeared in 1979 TV film ''Dallas Cowboys Cheerleaders'' alongside [[Jane Seymour (actress)|Jane Seymour]] and made her film debut in the 1981 movie ''[[Eyes of a Stranger (1981 film)|Eyes of a Stranger]]'', which co-starred a young [[Jennifer Jason Leigh]]. \n\nIn 1984, after seven seasons, Tewes was replaced on ''The Love Boat'' after a highly public battle with cocaine addiction (and associated weight gain)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dangaard|first=Colin|date=25 March 1982|title=Lauren Tewes Cooking up a Storm|url=https://gleaner.newspaperarchive.com/kingston-gleaner/1982-03-23/page-4/|journal=Kingston Gleaner|volume=|pages=4|via=}}</ref> which began recreationally in 1977 but which she eventually overcame.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-RsNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=k2YDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4543,4421645&dq=lauren+tewes+cocaine|title=\"Cocaine Abuse Threw Tewes' Performance Overboard\"|last=|first=|date=12 March 1985|work=St. Petersburg Times|access-date=1 April 2019}}</ref>  She did reprise her role as a guest in a 1985 episode.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LA&p_theme=la&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EF5B911B4C3C3C7&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Lauren Tewes Takes Cruise For Old Time's Sake|date=November 26, 1985|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=2009-01-08}}</ref> \n\nTewes was cast in a 1985 [[CBS]] sitcom pilot ''Anything for Love''. The pilot aired as a special that summer, but was not picked up as a series. She went on to star in classic 1980s TV series [[Mickey Spillane's Mike Hammer (1984 TV series)|''The New Mike Hammer'']], ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]'', ''[[T.J. Hooker]]'' and [[Hunter (1984 U.S. TV series)|''Hunter'']].  \n\nIn 1994, Tewes moved to Seattle and focused on regional theatre acting and directing across the country. In Seattle, she performed with the Tacoma Actors Guild and the Seattle Repertory Theatre.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/633256/Tewes-sets-a-new-course.html|title=Tewes sets a new course|last=Talerico|first=Teresa|date=31 May 1998|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|access-date=}}</ref>   As well as doing voice-overs for commercials, Tewes continued her TV career and appeared in a 1998 episode of ''[[Love Boat: The Next Wave]]'', a revival of the original series.  In 2000\u201301, she had a recurring role as a police detective on ''[[The Fugitive (2000 series)|The Fugitive]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/people/lauren-tewes/|title=Lauren Tewes|website=TV.com|publisher=CBS Interactive Inc.|date=2020|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTewes plays Maxine Murdoch in the ''[[Imagination Theatre]]'' comedy-mystery radio series ''Murder and the Murdochs'', which debuted in 2020. She has also played roles in episodes of other radio series on ''Imagination Theatre''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://harrynile.com/product-tag/cynthia-lauren-tewes/|title=Cynthia Lauren Tewes \u2013 Imagination Theatre|date=2020|website=Imagination Theatre|publisher=Aural Vision LLC|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Culinary school ==\nTewes attended culinary school to become a [[cheese]] specialist and, when she is not acting, she works as a [[sous-chef]] for a [[catering]] company in Seattle.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.illawarramercury.com.au/story/3170519/bon-voyage-love-boat-tribute/?cs=4644|title=The Love Boat Tribute|last=Brown|first=Emma|date=25 June 2015|work=Illawarra Mercury|access-date=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nTewes has been married three times, first to John Wassel, a TV commercials director, then to Paolo Nonnis, an Italian drummer, and finally stage actor Robert Nadir. In 1987, she suffered the loss of her one month-old daughter, born premature.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=AIUNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OW8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6514,3461816&dq=lauren+tewes+cocaine|title=Sailing a Different Course|date=February 24, 1998|publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|page=17|accessdate=January 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0856708}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tewes, Lauren}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actors from Whittier, California]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Braddock, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:University of California, Riverside alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Whittier, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image              = Lauren Tewes.jpg\n| caption            = Tewes in ''The Love Boat'', 1977\n| name               = Lauren Tewes\n| birth_place        = [[Braddock, Allegheny County, Pennsylvania|Braddock, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1953|10|26}}\n| known_for          = Julie McCoy \u2013 ''[[The Love Boat]]''\n| education          = [[Rio Hondo College]]<br>[[University of California, Riverside]] (withdrawn)\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| othername           = \n| occupation          = Actress \n| yearsactive        = 1976\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|John Wassel<br>|1977|1982|end=divorced}}<br>Paolo Nonnis<br>({{abbr|m.|married}} 1985; {{abbr|div.|divorced}} 1995)<br>{{marriage|Robert Nadir<br>|1996|2002|end=died}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Love boat cast 1977.JPG|thumb|upright|Tewes with fellow ''Love Boat'' cast members]]\n\n'''Cynthia Lauren Tewes''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|w|i\u02d0|z}}; born October 26, 1953) is an [[Americans|American]] actress. She is best known for her role as Julie McCoy on the [[television comedy]] [[anthology series]] ''[[The Love Boat]]'', which originally aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] from 1977\u201386.\n\n==Early years==\nTewes was born in [[Braddock, Allegheny County, Pennsylvania|Braddock, Pennsylvania]], of German extraction and one of 4 children, to Joanne (n\u00e9e Woods) and Joseph Robert Tewes, a wood pattern maker.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rZ4UuQ5N_SEC&q=%22daughter+of+Joseph+(a+wood+pattern+maker)+and+Joanne+(Woods)+Tewes.%22&dq=%22daughter+of+Joseph+(a+wood+pattern+maker)+and+Joanne+(Woods)+Tewes.%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=sbxaVca1N4iwsAS9xYGQCg&ved=0CBMQ6AEwAA|title=Contemporary Theatre, Film and Television|first=Monica M.|last=O'Donnell|date=8 March 1984|publisher=Gale|via=Google Books}}</ref>  Her early childhood was spent in industrial [[Trafford, Pennsylvania|Trafford]], near Pittsburgh before the family moved to [[Whittier, California]] when she was 8. \n\nTewes attended Ada S. Nelson Elementary School<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=24 March 1978|title=Lauren Tewes|url=|journal=Cumberland Evening Times|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> and [[Pioneer High School (Whittier, California)|Pioneer High School]] where she studied Drama, winning Best Actress award for 3 years.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dangaard|first=Colin|date=23 March 1982|title=Lauren Tewes Cooking up a Storm|url=https://gleaner.newspaperarchive.com/kingston-gleaner/1982-03-23/page-4/|journal=Kingston Gleaner|volume=|pages=4|via=}}</ref> Tewes enrolled on an [[Associate degree|associate of arts]] degree at [[Rio Hondo College]], deciding to major in Theatre Arts.  At college, she won \"The Chancellor's Award for Excellence in Theatre\", a one-year scholarship which enabled her to transfer to the [[University of California, Riverside]] as a sophomore.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://traffordhistory.org/lookingback/index.php/world-war-i-veterans/91-family-life/112-tewes|title=Lauren Tewes -- Hollywood Success|last=|first=|date=Jun 24, 1979|work=The Morning News|access-date=}}</ref>  \n\nIn 1973, when her scholarship expired, Tewes withdrew from university and joined the [[Pacific Conservatory of the Performing Arts|Pacific Conservatory Theatre]] in Santa Maria, California as an apprentice making her stage debut in ''[[Arsenic and Old Lace (play)|Arsenic and Old Lace]]'' and ''[[The Most Happy Fella]]'' before becoming a member of the Birdcage Theatre Company at [[Knott's Berry Farm]], an amusement complex outside Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://traffordhistory.org/lookingback/index.php/world-war-i-veterans/91-family-life/112-tewes|title=She Won't Rock The \"Love Boat\" - ABC's Hit Series Serenely Sails On|last=Peterson|first=Bettelou|date=Aug 19, 1979|work=Detroit Free Press|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nTewe's first break came in mid-1974 when she starred in a [[Lipton Ice Tea]] commercial, allowing her to join the [[Screen Actors Guild]] and register with an agent with the prospect to work on film projects.  \n\nIn 1975, whilst waitressing in Sunset Boulevard coffee shops and penniless, she suffered a traumatic loss when her mother was diagnosed with terminal cancer and died a year later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title='Love Boat's' Star's Hearbreaking Memory: Her Mom's Last Christmas|last=Troll|first=Harriett|date=8 September 1981|work=Weekly World News|access-date=}}</ref>    \n\nTewes obtained minor parts in TV series ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'' and ''[[Family (1976 TV series)|Family]]'' (\"Mirror, Mirror on the Wall...\") as Jill Redfield, a disenchanted Pasadena debutante. However, it was her role in ''[[Starsky and Hutch]]'' (\"Starsky and Hutch are guilty\") as Sharon Freemont, an assistant attorney which brought her to the attention of [[Aaron Spelling]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Will The Real \"Julie\" Please Stand Up?|last=|first=|date=|work=Cruise Travel; September/October 1980|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nTewes was cast for the role of cruise director Julie McCoy on ''[[The Love Boat]],'' selected from more than 100 actresses who auditioned.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-RsNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=k2YDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4543,4421645&dq=lauren+tewes+cocaine|title=Cocaine Abuse Threw Tewes' Performance Overboard|last=UPI|date=March 12, 1985|publisher=St. Petersburg Times|accessdate=2009-01-08}}</ref> She starred in the third and final pilot of the show, cast the day before production began on the [[RMS Queen Mary|RMS ''Queen Mary'']] in San Pedro.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19820219&id=soQsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wc0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2167,3714630|title=Lauren Tewes To Cruise For Two More Years|last=AP|date=February 19, 1982|publisher=Spartanburg Herald-Journal}}</ref> Tewes recalls the pilot episode:\n\n\"I had to borrow money to get a new tire, because my \u201962 Volkswagen Bug was not going to get to San Pedro\u2026. That first day, standing there in the little outfit, and I had to say, \u201dHi, welcome aboard, I\u2019m Julie McCoy, your cruise director\u201d a gazillion times. But I kept screwing it up and saying, \u201dHi, welcome aboard, I\u2019m Julie MacLeod\u2026\u201d because I was talking to Gavin MacLeod and I was so excited.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2007/10/07/love-boat-cast-and-crew-tell-all/|title='Love Boat': Cast and crew tell all|last=Snierson|first=Dan|date=7 October 2007|website=Entertainment}}</ref>   \n\nIn parallel, Tewes appeared in 1979 TV film ''Dallas Cowboys Cheerleaders'' alongside [[Jane Seymour (actress)|Jane Seymour]] and made her film debut in the 1981 movie ''[[Eyes of a Stranger (1981 film)|Eyes of a Stranger]]'', which co-starred a young [[Jennifer Jason Leigh]]. \n\nIn 1984, after seven seasons, Tewes was replaced on ''The Love Boat'' after a highly public battle with cocaine addiction (and associated weight gain)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dangaard|first=Colin|date=25 March 1982|title=Lauren Tewes Cooking up a Storm|url=https://gleaner.newspaperarchive.com/kingston-gleaner/1982-03-23/page-4/|journal=Kingston Gleaner|volume=|pages=4|via=}}</ref> which began recreationally in 1977 but which she eventually overcame.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-RsNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=k2YDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4543,4421645&dq=lauren+tewes+cocaine|title=\"Cocaine Abuse Threw Tewes' Performance Overboard\"|last=|first=|date=12 March 1985|work=St. Petersburg Times|access-date=1 April 2019}}</ref>  She did reprise her role as a guest in a 1985 episode.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LA&p_theme=la&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EF5B911B4C3C3C7&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Lauren Tewes Takes Cruise For Old Time's Sake|date=November 26, 1985|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=2009-01-08}}</ref> \n\nTewes was cast in a 1985 [[CBS]] sitcom pilot ''Anything for Love''. The pilot aired as a special that summer, but was not picked up as a series. She went on to star in classic 1980s TV series [[Mickey Spillane's Mike Hammer (1984 TV series)|''The New Mike Hammer'']], ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]'', ''[[T.J. Hooker]]'' and [[Hunter (1984 U.S. TV series)|''Hunter'']].  \n\nIn 1994, Tewes moved to Seattle and focused on regional theatre acting and directing across the country. In Seattle, she performed with the Tacoma Actors Guild and the Seattle Repertory Theatre.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/633256/Tewes-sets-a-new-course.html|title=Tewes sets a new course|last=Talerico|first=Teresa|date=31 May 1998|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|access-date=}}</ref>   As well as doing voice-overs for commercials, Tewes continued her TV career and appeared in a 1998 episode of ''[[Love Boat: The Next Wave]]'', a revival of the original series.  In 2000\u201301, she had a recurring role as a police detective on ''[[The Fugitive (2000 series)|The Fugitive]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/people/lauren-tewes/|title=Lauren Tewes|website=TV.com|publisher=CBS Interactive Inc.|date=2020|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTewes plays Maxine Murdoch in the ''[[Imagination Theatre]]'' comedy-mystery radio series ''Murder and the Murdochs'', which debuted in 2020. She has also played roles in episodes of other radio series on ''Imagination Theatre''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://harrynile.com/product-tag/cynthia-lauren-tewes/|title=Cynthia Lauren Tewes \u2013\u00a0Imagination Theatre|date=2020|website=Imagination Theatre|publisher=Aural Vision LLC|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Culinary school ==\nTewes attended culinary school to become a [[cheese]] specialist and, when she is not acting, she works as a [[sous-chef]] for a [[catering]] company in Seattle.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.illawarramercury.com.au/story/3170519/bon-voyage-love-boat-tribute/?cs=4644|title=The Love Boat Tribute|last=Brown|first=Emma|date=25 June 2015|work=Illawarra Mercury|access-date=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nTewes has been married three times, first to John Wassel, a TV commercials director, then to Paolo Nonnis, an Italian drummer, and finally stage actor Robert Nadir. In 1987, she suffered the loss of her one month-old daughter, born premature.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=AIUNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OW8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6514,3461816&dq=lauren+tewes+cocaine|title=Sailing a Different Course|date=February 24, 1998|publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|page=17|accessdate=January 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0856708}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tewes, Lauren}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actors from Whittier, California]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Braddock, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:University of California, Riverside alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Whittier, California]]\n", "name_user": "Miles26", "label": "safe", "comment": "spacing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lauren_Tewes"}
{"title_page": "Sandor Zicherman", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = #6495ED\n| name          = Sandor Zicherman\n| image         = File:Zicherman Sandor Robert.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| alt           = photographic portrait of an older white man with a long grey beard\n| caption       = Sandor Zicherman\n| birth_name    = Sandor Zicherman\n| birth_date    = 1935\n| birth_place   = [[Uzhhorod|U\u017ehorod]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Hungarian\n| field         = \n| training      = \n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced by = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = \n| website       = {{URL|http://www.zicherman.eu/}}\n}}\n'''Sandor Zicherman''' ({{lang-ru|'''\u0428\u0430\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0440 \u0417\u0438\u0445\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d'''}}) (born 1935, U\u017ehorod, Czechoslovakia, (now [[Uzhhorod, Ukraine]])) is a Soviet and Hungarian artist.\n\nZicherman has been a member of the [[Union of Russian Artists]] since 1965,<ref>{{cite web |url= |title=\u041a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0433\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0438 \u0421\u0430\u043c\u0430\u0440\u044b |trans-title=Cultural Heroes of Samara |work=Samru (Samara News) }} {{in lang|ru}}</ref> and is a member of the MAOE (Association of Hungarian Creators), the Association of Hungarian Fine and Applied Artists, the Hungarian Sculptor's Society, the [[World Artists Association]], the AIAP (Association International des Arts Plastiques), and FIDEM (International Art Medal Federation). His works have been displayed at [[Hermitage Museum|The Hermitage]] and many other museums.<ref name=museum_news>{{cite web |url=http://www.museum.ru/N31232 |title=\"\u041a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0430 \u0412\u0435\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0438\u0438\" \u0432 \u0421\u0430\u043c\u0430\u0440\u0435 |trans-title=\"Culture of Hungary\" in Samara |work=Museum News |publisher=Russian Cultural Heritage Network |accessdate=March 31, 2014}} {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n\nHe lives in Budapest, Hungary.  He is married to an actress, Zinaida Zicherman, and has two daughters and two sons.\n\n==Life==\nS\u00e1ndor Robert Zicherman was born on the 6th of April 1935 in Uzhgorod. He spent his childhood and started his studies in [[Berehove]] (Beregsz\u00e1sz) which is now located at the Ukrainian-Hungarian border.\n\nIn 1957, as a self-taught painter, he participated in his first exhibition at the Gallery of Fine Arts in Uzhgorod. In 1958 he was accepted to the [[The Lviv National Academy of Arts|College of Arts and Crafts]] in [[Lwow]] and started his professional studies at the faculty of monumental painting.{{clarify|reason=\"monumental painting\", what is that? Do they really have a department dedicated to very large paintings?|date=March 2014}} After the first year he moved to [[Leningrad]] where he continued his studies at the Vera Mukhina Higher School of Art and Design (now the [[Saint Petersburg State Art and Industry Academy]]), also at the monumental painting faculty.{{clarify|reason=\"monumental painting\"... what is it?|date=March 2014}}\n\nAfter graduating in 1964, Zicherman moved to [[Perm]] in the [[Ural Mountains|Ural region]], where he worked for the Fine Arts Foundation on a number of commissions, as a specialist in monumental art.{{clarify|reason=again with the \"monumental arts\"... monuments? very large works? progaganda? public art? or what?|date=March 2014}} In Perm and the surrounding region he produced a number of [[fresco]]s, [[mosaic]]s, [[sgraffito]]s, and ceramic [[high relief]]s, and also three large gobelins (tapestries after the manner of the [[Gobelins Manufactory|Gobelins]]). \n\nIn addition to executing works linked to architecture, Zicherman also worked for Perm Television and the Perm theatres. In 1966, after participating in the art exhibition \"Socialist Urals\" sponsored by the [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian Soviet Republic]] he was accepted to the [[USSR Union of Artists]] as a candidate member, and in 1975 as a full member. Between 1969 and 1972 he worked and lived in a number of different cities and regions including Lviv, [[J\u016brmala]], [[Riga]], [[Elista]], and [[Moscow]].\n\nIn 1972 Zicherman moved to [[Tolyatti]] (formerly Stavropol-on-Volga) at the invitation of the city administration for the organization of cultural and artistic life. He contributed to the founding of the Tolyatti Lyceum of Arts art gallery,<ref name=museum_news/> and was instrumental in founding the Tolyatti branch of the Union of Artists. In 1987, he organized Russia's first stone-carving sculpture symposium, in Tolyatti.\n\nZicherman later moved to [[Samara, Russia|Samara]], where he married Zinaida Sokolova,<ref name=museum_news/> and in 1989 to [[Budapest]]. Of this move to [[Hungary]], he said that \"[A]ll of us are of mixed nationalities, I do not know a single person who is one hundred percent Russian or [[Mordovia]]n\". He describes himself as a Hungarian artist of Russian origin.<ref>[http://mordovia.spravedlivo.ru/press/smi_review/230.smx Art Exhibit at Yalgat]{{in lang|ru}} {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080716064900/http://mordovia.spravedlivo.ru/press/smi_review/230.smx |date=July 16, 2008 }}</ref> In Budapest, he and his wife opened a Russian theater and studio at the Russian embassy.<ref>[http://www.szinhaz.hu/rusteatr/rufolap.shtml History of the Russian Theatre-Studio]{{in lang|hu}} {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060615001523/http://www.szinhaz.hu/rusteatr/rufolap.shtml |date=June 15, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nBy 1989 Sandor Zicherman had participated in great number All-Soviet and All-Russian exhibitions, including exhibitions representing Soviet art abroad (Hungary, Czechoslovakia, NDK, Poland). His exhibits included paintings to graphics, medals, ceramics, sculptures, and tapestries. His mosaics, sgraffitos and memorials are still on show in many Russian cities. In addition to participating in group exhibitions, by 1989 he had had more than 30 personal exhibitions in various cities of the Soviet Union and also participated in 13 different Soviet or international two-month symposiums. Since his move to Budapest in 1990 he has participated in more than 60 group and personal exhibitions in Budapest and other Hungarian cities, as well as a great number of European countries.\n\nZicherman does not adhere to a particular genre; among his works and graphics are portraits, [[avant-garde]] pieces, and classical landscapes, employing a variety of stylistic devices such as [[cubo-futurism]], [[post-impressionism]], and [[realism (visual arts)|realism]]. In recent years, he has produced many works in the [[Depictions of nudity|nu]] genre.\n\nHis work is represented in [[Hermitage Museum|The Hermitage]], the Samara State Fine Arts Museum, the Tolyatti Art Museum, the Museum of Regional Ethnography in Perm, the Museum of Fine Arts of the [[Udmurt Republic]], the Technical Museum of Autovaz in Tolyatti, the Museum of Fine Arts of the [[Mari El Republic]] in [[Yoshkar-Ola]], the Joseph Boksay Fine Art Museum of Transcarpathia in Uzhgorod, the Kalmyk Fine Art Museum in Elista, the Museum of Medal Art in [[Wroclaw]], the War History Museum in Budapest, and many other museums in Europe.\n\nEvery year, Zicherman returns to Russia, where he holds a regular solo exhibition. In 2006, there was an exhibition of his works in Tolyatti, dedicated to the fortieth anniversary of [[AvtoVAZ]]. In 2007, the show was held in Samara.\n\nZicherman's work has sometimes been the target of thieves. In the early 1990s, he was one of the organizers of an exhibit from whence 171 pieces were stolen. In Samara, a plaque by Zicherman in honor of the 100th birthday of [[People's Artist]] [[George Shebuev]] was stolen, and in Tolyatti, a two-meter pink marble sculpture by Zicherman was stolen too.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.samaratoday.ru/news/89945/ |title=\u0412 \u0422\u043e\u043b\u044c\u044f\u0442\u0442\u0438 \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u0432\u044b\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0445\u0443\u0434\u043e\u0436\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u0441\u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u043f\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u0428\u0430\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u0417\u0438\u0445\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0430 |trans-title=Exhibition by the artist and sculptor S\u00e1ndor Zicherman opens in Tolyatti|date=July 20, 2006 |work=Samara Today |accessdate=March 31, 2014}} {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120308052231/http://www.vdmst.ru/25-07-2006/3947 Review of Zicherman exhibition, ''Tolyatti City Gazette''  '''(Russian)''']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110928132952/http://old.samara.ru/paper/41/6246/108698/?printable Review of Zicherman exhibition in Samara '''(Russian)''']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120308052232/http://www.ps.avtograd.ru/Print.asp?ID=51308 Review of Zicherman exhibition, Tolyatti newspaper ''Freedom Square'' '''(Russian)''' ]\n* [http://www.aki-ros.ru/default.asp?Part=256&NID=18244 Review of Zicherman exhibition, CNA (Agency of Cultural Information) '''(Russian)''']{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://chronograf.ru/articles/?num=26&a=587 Review of Zicherman exhibition, Tolyatti ''Chronograph'' '''(Russian)''']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120322230116/http://www.ladanews.ru/cgi-bin/lnews.pl?inf=lnews1.inf&step=print&bind1=499308&number=201 Review of Zicherman exhibition, Diana Stukanova, Volga Automobile Manufacturers' ''ladanews.ru'' '''(Russian)''']\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zicherman, Sandor}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Soviet artists]]\n[[Category:Russian artists]]\n[[Category:Hungarian artists]]\n[[Category:Czechoslovak people]]\n[[Category:People from Uzhhorod]]\n[[Category:People from Tolyatti]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = #6495ED\n| name          = Sandor Zicherman\n| image         = File:Zicherman Sandor Robert.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| alt           = photographic portrait of an older white man with a long grey beard\n| caption       = Sandor Zicherman\n| birth_name    = Sandor Zicherman\n| birth_date    = 1935\n| birth_place   = [[Uzhhorod]], [[Ukraine]] \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Hungarian\n| field         = \n| training      = \n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced by = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = \n| website       = {{URL|http://www.zicherman.eu/}}\n}}\n'''Sandor Zicherman''' ({{lang-ru|'''\u0428\u0430\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0440 \u0417\u0438\u0445\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d'''}}) (born 1935, U\u017ehorod, Czechoslovakia, (now [[Uzhhorod, Ukraine]])) is a Soviet and Hungarian artist.\n\nZicherman has been a member of the [[Union of Russian Artists]] since 1965,<ref>{{cite web |url= |title=\u041a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0433\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0438 \u0421\u0430\u043c\u0430\u0440\u044b |trans-title=Cultural Heroes of Samara |work=Samru (Samara News) }} {{in lang|ru}}</ref> and is a member of the MAOE (Association of Hungarian Creators), the Association of Hungarian Fine and Applied Artists, the Hungarian Sculptor's Society, the [[World Artists Association]], the AIAP (Association International des Arts Plastiques), and FIDEM (International Art Medal Federation). His works have been displayed at [[Hermitage Museum|The Hermitage]] and many other museums.<ref name=museum_news>{{cite web |url=http://www.museum.ru/N31232 |title=\"\u041a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0430 \u0412\u0435\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0438\u0438\" \u0432 \u0421\u0430\u043c\u0430\u0440\u0435 |trans-title=\"Culture of Hungary\" in Samara |work=Museum News |publisher=Russian Cultural Heritage Network |accessdate=March 31, 2014}} {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n\nHe lives in Budapest, Hungary.  He is married to an actress, Zinaida Zicherman, and has two daughters and two sons.\n\n==Life==\nS\u00e1ndor Robert Zicherman was born on the 6th of April 1935 in Uzhgorod. He spent his childhood and started his studies in [[Berehove]] (Beregsz\u00e1sz) which is now located at the Ukrainian-Hungarian border.\n\nIn 1957, as a self-taught painter, he participated in his first exhibition at the Gallery of Fine Arts in Uzhgorod. In 1958 he was accepted to the [[The Lviv National Academy of Arts|College of Arts and Crafts]] in [[Lwow]] and started his professional studies at the faculty of monumental painting.{{clarify|reason=\"monumental painting\", what is that? Do they really have a department dedicated to very large paintings?|date=March 2014}} After the first year he moved to [[Leningrad]] where he continued his studies at the Vera Mukhina Higher School of Art and Design (now the [[Saint Petersburg State Art and Industry Academy]]), also at the monumental painting faculty.{{clarify|reason=\"monumental painting\"... what is it?|date=March 2014}}\n\nAfter graduating in 1964, Zicherman moved to [[Perm]] in the [[Ural Mountains|Ural region]], where he worked for the Fine Arts Foundation on a number of commissions, as a specialist in monumental art.{{clarify|reason=again with the \"monumental arts\"... monuments? very large works? progaganda? public art? or what?|date=March 2014}} In Perm and the surrounding region he produced a number of [[fresco]]s, [[mosaic]]s, [[sgraffito]]s, and ceramic [[high relief]]s, and also three large gobelins (tapestries after the manner of the [[Gobelins Manufactory|Gobelins]]). \n\nIn addition to executing works linked to architecture, Zicherman also worked for Perm Television and the Perm theatres. In 1966, after participating in the art exhibition \"Socialist Urals\" sponsored by the [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian Soviet Republic]] he was accepted to the [[USSR Union of Artists]] as a candidate member, and in 1975 as a full member. Between 1969 and 1972 he worked and lived in a number of different cities and regions including Lviv, [[J\u016brmala]], [[Riga]], [[Elista]], and [[Moscow]].\n\nIn 1972 Zicherman moved to [[Tolyatti]] (formerly Stavropol-on-Volga) at the invitation of the city administration for the organization of cultural and artistic life. He contributed to the founding of the Tolyatti Lyceum of Arts art gallery,<ref name=museum_news/> and was instrumental in founding the Tolyatti branch of the Union of Artists. In 1987, he organized Russia's first stone-carving sculpture symposium, in Tolyatti.\n\nZicherman later moved to [[Samara, Russia|Samara]], where he married Zinaida Sokolova,<ref name=museum_news/> and in 1989 to [[Budapest]]. Of this move to [[Hungary]], he said that \"[A]ll of us are of mixed nationalities, I do not know a single person who is one hundred percent Russian or [[Mordovia]]n\". He describes himself as a Hungarian artist of Russian origin.<ref>[http://mordovia.spravedlivo.ru/press/smi_review/230.smx Art Exhibit at Yalgat]{{in lang|ru}} {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080716064900/http://mordovia.spravedlivo.ru/press/smi_review/230.smx |date=July 16, 2008 }}</ref> In Budapest, he and his wife opened a Russian theater and studio at the Russian embassy.<ref>[http://www.szinhaz.hu/rusteatr/rufolap.shtml History of the Russian Theatre-Studio]{{in lang|hu}} {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060615001523/http://www.szinhaz.hu/rusteatr/rufolap.shtml |date=June 15, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nBy 1989 Sandor Zicherman had participated in great number All-Soviet and All-Russian exhibitions, including exhibitions representing Soviet art abroad (Hungary, Czechoslovakia, NDK, Poland). His exhibits included paintings to graphics, medals, ceramics, sculptures, and tapestries. His mosaics, sgraffitos and memorials are still on show in many Russian cities. In addition to participating in group exhibitions, by 1989 he had had more than 30 personal exhibitions in various cities of the Soviet Union and also participated in 13 different Soviet or international two-month symposiums. Since his move to Budapest in 1990 he has participated in more than 60 group and personal exhibitions in Budapest and other Hungarian cities, as well as a great number of European countries.\n\nZicherman does not adhere to a particular genre; among his works and graphics are portraits, [[avant-garde]] pieces, and classical landscapes, employing a variety of stylistic devices such as [[cubo-futurism]], [[post-impressionism]], and [[realism (visual arts)|realism]]. In recent years, he has produced many works in the [[Depictions of nudity|nu]] genre.\n\nHis work is represented in [[Hermitage Museum|The Hermitage]], the Samara State Fine Arts Museum, the Tolyatti Art Museum, the Museum of Regional Ethnography in Perm, the Museum of Fine Arts of the [[Udmurt Republic]], the Technical Museum of Autovaz in Tolyatti, the Museum of Fine Arts of the [[Mari El Republic]] in [[Yoshkar-Ola]], the Joseph Boksay Fine Art Museum of Transcarpathia in Uzhgorod, the Kalmyk Fine Art Museum in Elista, the Museum of Medal Art in [[Wroclaw]], the War History Museum in Budapest, and many other museums in Europe.\n\nEvery year, Zicherman returns to Russia, where he holds a regular solo exhibition. In 2006, there was an exhibition of his works in Tolyatti, dedicated to the fortieth anniversary of [[AvtoVAZ]]. In 2007, the show was held in Samara.\n\nZicherman's work has sometimes been the target of thieves. In the early 1990s, he was one of the organizers of an exhibit from whence 171 pieces were stolen. In Samara, a plaque by Zicherman in honor of the 100th birthday of [[People's Artist]] [[George Shebuev]] was stolen, and in Tolyatti, a two-meter pink marble sculpture by Zicherman was stolen too.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.samaratoday.ru/news/89945/ |title=\u0412 \u0422\u043e\u043b\u044c\u044f\u0442\u0442\u0438 \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u0432\u044b\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0445\u0443\u0434\u043e\u0436\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u0441\u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u043f\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u0428\u0430\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u0417\u0438\u0445\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0430 |trans-title=Exhibition by the artist and sculptor S\u00e1ndor Zicherman opens in Tolyatti|date=July 20, 2006 |work=Samara Today |accessdate=March 31, 2014}} {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120308052231/http://www.vdmst.ru/25-07-2006/3947 Review of Zicherman exhibition, ''Tolyatti City Gazette''  '''(Russian)''']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110928132952/http://old.samara.ru/paper/41/6246/108698/?printable Review of Zicherman exhibition in Samara '''(Russian)''']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120308052232/http://www.ps.avtograd.ru/Print.asp?ID=51308 Review of Zicherman exhibition, Tolyatti newspaper ''Freedom Square'' '''(Russian)''' ]\n* [http://www.aki-ros.ru/default.asp?Part=256&NID=18244 Review of Zicherman exhibition, CNA (Agency of Cultural Information) '''(Russian)''']{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://chronograf.ru/articles/?num=26&a=587 Review of Zicherman exhibition, Tolyatti ''Chronograph'' '''(Russian)''']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120322230116/http://www.ladanews.ru/cgi-bin/lnews.pl?inf=lnews1.inf&step=print&bind1=499308&number=201 Review of Zicherman exhibition, Diana Stukanova, Volga Automobile Manufacturers' ''ladanews.ru'' '''(Russian)''']\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zicherman, Sandor}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Soviet artists]]\n[[Category:Russian artists]]\n[[Category:Hungarian artists]]\n[[Category:Czechoslovak people]]\n[[Category:People from Uzhhorod]]\n[[Category:People from Tolyatti]]\