{"title_page": "Lele Pons", "text_new": "{{For|the opera singer|Lily Pons}}\n{{Spanish name|Pons|Maronese}}{{Use American English|date = January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = January 2020}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name               = Lele Pons\n| image              = Lele Pons 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| image_size         = 200\n| caption            = Lele Pons at the 2019 iHeartRadio Music Awards in Los Angeles, California\n| birth_name         = Eleonora Pons Maronese\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1996|6|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Caracas]], Venezuela\n| origin             = [[Miami|Miami, Florida]], U.S.\n| nationality        = American, Venezuelan<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BzgYEp8poB4/|title=Lele Pons on Instagram: \"Happy 4th of July\ud83d\udca5\ud83c\uddfa\ud83c\uddf8 Guess who became an American citizen ?? Now I\u2019m both a citizen in Venezuela and in the United States!! \u2764\ufe0f\u2764\ufe0f\u2764\ufe0f\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n| occupation         = {{hlist|[[YouTuber]]|actress|singer|dancer|model}}\n| years_active       = 2013\u2013present\n| channel_direct_url = LelePons\n| genre              = Comedy\n| subscribers        = 16 million\n| subscriber_date    = March 2020\n| silver_button      = yes\n| silver_year        = 2016\n| gold_button        = yes\n| gold_year          = 2016\n| diamond_button     = yes\n| diamond_year       = 2018\n}}\n\n'''Eleonora''' \"'''Lele'''\" '''Pons Maronese''' (born June 25, 1996) is an American-Venezuelan fake celebrity, YouTuber, actress, singer, dancer, model and former host of ''[[La Voz... M\u00e9xico]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O9gzqC5gj3E |title=FIRST Q&A ANSWERED BY FRIENDS |last1=Pons |first1=Lele |date=June 15, 2016 |via=YouTube |accessdate=July 31, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2018/05/16/lele-pons-la-voz-the-voice-mexico/|title=Social Star Lele Pons Will Host The Mexican Version Of \u2018The Voice\u2019|last=Gutelle|first=Sam|date=May 16, 2018|work=TubeFilter|access-date=June 27, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/lele-pons-la-voz-mexico-host-1202811755/|title=Internet Star Lele Pons Named Host of Televisa\u2019s \u2018La Voz M\u00e9xico\u2019 Singing Competition|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=May 16, 2018|work=Variety|access-date=July 10, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\nPons came to prominence on [[Vine (service)|Vine]] before the platform shut down in 2016. She has since branched out, creating comedy sketches for [[YouTube]], where she now has over 16 million subscribers, and 38.6 million followers on [[Instagram]]. She has acted in film, television and in music videos, has released her own music, and co-authored a novel in 2016.\n\n==Early life==\nPons was born in [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]]. Pons moved to the [[United States]] at the age of five and was raised in [[Miami]], [[Florida]]. She graduated from [[Miami Country Day School]] in 2015 and moved to [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]. She has said that she had trouble making friends in high school, so she \"would get hurt to make them laugh.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thecut.com/2017/04/youtube-star-lele-pons-the-most-popular-girl-in-hollywood.html|title=Lele Pons Is One Fart Joke Away From World Domination|last=Jones|first=Allie|date=April 18, 2017|work=The Cut|access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref> She has also said that she was bullied at high school. She said \"I'm not like the cool girls\u2014I'm the ''other'' girl. The one that's basically a nerd, but proud of that.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/lele-pons-vine-star-interview|title=Exclusive! Get to Know Lele Pons, the Girl Behind Those Vines You Can't Stop Watching|last=Firman|first=Tehrene|date=February 19, 2015|work=Teen Vogue|access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nPons began her career on the six-second video platform [[Vine (service)|Vine]]. She has said she used Vine to showcase the creative things she was already doing. Speaking to ''[[Teen Vogue]]'', Pons said, \"I started with my friends, and I started becoming bad. At first it was just being really creative - it wasn't even funny stuff.\" Her follower base continued to grow and Pons has said that it \"got to the point where a lot of people depended on me to make them... just so they could get a laugh.\" She became the first \"Viner\" to reach one billion loops.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nWriting in ''[[The Cut (magazine)|The Cut]]'', Allie Jones described Pons' comedy as \"universal, physical, and complete with a twist ending.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Pons' comedic style has also been criticised. For instance, former Viner, Cody Ko, critically viewed one her sketches, saying, \"This was written by a four-year-old.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/internet-community-turning-lele-pons-formerly-worlds-1-viner-2271864|title=How the internet community is turning on Lele Pons, formerly the world's #1 Viner|last=Bartleet|first=Larry|date=March 23, 2018|work=NME|access-date=June 17, 2018}}</ref> Pons cites, among her inspirations, several Latina stars including [[Sof\u00eda Vergara]], [[Gaby Espino]], and [[Shakira]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2016, she was signed with entertainment company [[Shots Studios]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8015077/shots-studios-profile-alesso-lele-pons-rudy-mancuso|title=How Shots Studios Plans to Take Over the Music Industry|last=Armstrong|first=Megan|date=January 11, 2017|work=Billboard|access-date=September 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPons is managed by [[John Shahidi]] of [[Shots Studios]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.producthunt.com/who-is-john-shahidi-and-why-shots-exists-1f14d01d5819|title=Who is John Shahidi and Why Shots Studios Exists|last=Hunt|first=Product|date=2018-03-28|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nPons has used her success in Internet comedy to launch a number of enterprises. In 2015, she launched a jewelry collection called UNO Magnetic.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2016, Pons co-authored a novel based on her own high school experiences, ''Surviving High School'', co-authored with [[Melissa de la Cruz]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/Surviving-High-School/Lele-Pons/9781501120541|title=Surviving High School|last=|first=|date=|website=Simon & Schuster|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref> Pons starred as Callie in the 2016 romantic comedy ''We Love You'', released on [[YouTube Premium|YouTube Red]]. In the movie, characters played by [[Yousef Erakat]] and Justin Dobies both fall for Pons, who is \"cool enough\" to date both of them at the same time.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/fouseytube-lele-pons-youtube-awesomenesstv-we-love-you-1201737499/|title=YouTube, AwesomenessTV 'We Love You' Movie to Star FouseyTube, Lele Pons|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=March 23, 2016|work=Variety|access-date=June 17, 2018}}</ref> The movie was produced by YouTube and [[AwesomenessTV]].\n\nPons appeared in the first episode of [[MTV]]'s horror TV series, ''[[Scream (TV series)|Scream]]'', in which she was the season's first victim.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2879929/scream-season-2-premiere-opening/|title=The First 7 Minutes of Scream's Season Two Premiere Is Here|last=Debler|first=Lance|date=May 13, 2016|work=MTV|access-date=June 17, 2018}}</ref> She has starred in a number of music videos, including \"[[Havana (Camila Cabello song)|Havana]]\" by [[Camila Cabello]], and \"[[Downtown (Anitta and J Balvin song)|Downtown]]\" by [[Anitta (singer)|Anitta]] and [[J Balvin]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://people.com/chica/who-is-lele-pons/|title=5 Reasons to Love Internet Sensation Lele Pons|last=Hansen|first=Lena|date=January 31, 2018|work=People Chica|access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref> In May 2018, Pons released her debut single, a Spanish-language duet with [[Matt Hunter (singer)|Matt Hunter]] titled \"Dicen.\" The YouTube music video amassed 10 million views in just four days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2018/05/07/lele-pons-debut-music-video-dicen/|title=Lele Pons Drops Debut Music Video, Clocking 10 Million Views In 4 Days|last=|first=|date=|work=TubeFilter|access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref> Pons has also had success in modelling. In February 2017, she became a brand ambassador for [[CoverGirl]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.twistmagazine.com/posts/lele-pons-covergirl-web-star-names-new-face-of-cosmetics-brand-125107|title=So Exciting: Lele Pons Is the Newest CoverGirl|last=Kowalski|first=Kristine Hope|date=February 10, 2017|work=Twist|access-date=June 17, 2018}}</ref> The same month, Pons walked in a Dolce & Gabbana show in Milan. ''[[The Tab|Babe]]'' criticised the move as seeming \"a bit hackneyed and past-it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://babe.net/2017/03/01/anyone-know-whats-happened-dolce-gabbana-550|title=Does anyone know what\u2019s happened to Dolce & Gabbana?|last=Lanigan|first=R\u00f3is\u00edn|date=March 1, 2017|work=Babe|access-date=June 17, 2018}}</ref> In August, Pons released her first single and music video for her song \"Celoso,\" which was directed by fellow creator Rudy Mancuso. The song was certified 3x Platinum and earned a nomination for the Premios Lo Nuestro nomination for the video.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/features/fl-reg-lele-pons-celoso-single-music-video-20180816-story.html |title=Youtube star Lele Pons debuts solo music video 'Celoso' |last=Diaz |first=Johnny |author-link=Johnny Diaz |date=August 17, 2018 |access-date=August 19, 2018 |newspaper=[[Sun Sentinel]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818120106/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/features/fl-reg-lele-pons-celoso-single-music-video-20180816-story.html |archive-date=August 18, 2018}}</ref> On March 29, 2019 Lele released her English-language debut, and her first [[country music|country]] song with the [[Jake Owen]] duet \"Se\u00f1orita\" from his album ''[[Greetings from... Jake]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.soundslikenashville.com/music/hear-jake-owens-sun-kissed-new-track-drink-all-day/|title=\nHear Jake Owen's Sun Kissed New Track 'Drink All Day' |last=Parton|first=Chris|date=March 15, 2019|work=Sounds Like Nashville|access-date=April 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nPons took over hosting of ''[[La Voz... M\u00e9xico]]'' on October 14, 2018.<ref name=\":3\" /> She presented the [[19th Annual Latin Grammy Awards]] with [[Aitana (singer)|Aitana]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://happyfm.es/musica/que-posibilidades-hay-de-que-aitana-y-lele-pons-actuen-en-los-latin-grammy-2018-166606/ |title=\u00bfQu\u00e9 posibilidad hay de que Aitana y Lele Pons act\u00faen en los Latin Grammy 2018? |first=Laura |last=Hern\u00e1ndez |date=November 14, 2018 |access-date=November 16, 2018 |work=Hapy FM}}</ref>\n\nOn December 6, 2019, Pons released her new single and music video \u201cVete Pa La.\u201d The music video was self-directed and edited by Pons and produced by Shots Studios.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1100293/the-mixtape-presents-harry-styles-camila-cabello-and-more-new-music-musts|title=The MixtapE! Presents Harry Styles, Camila Cabello and More New Music|date=December 6, 2019|website=E! Online|accessdate=2019-12-07}}</ref>\n\nOn December 2019, Pons was a co-host on the red carpet alongside Chelsea Briggs for the 2019 [[Billboard Women in Music]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8545988/meet-your-2019-billboard-women-in-music-hosts|title=Meet Your 2019 Billboard Women in Music Hosts|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref>\n\nPons was a guest speaker at the 2020 CES conference held in Las Vegas, NV. As a digital media mogul and global entertainer, Pons was asked to be a speaker on the [[Spotify]] panel alongside Spotify\u2019s Chief Content Officer [[Dawn Ostroff]]. She talked about how Spotify revolutionized music and impacted her career and how she plans on using that same model for her upcoming podcast with Spotify.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/lele-pons-paul-feig-dawn-ostroff-spotify-podcast-freaks-and-geeks-1203461460/|title=Lele Pons, Paul Feig and Spotify\u2019s Dawn Ostroff Talk Comedic Potential of Podcasts|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|last2=Littleton|first2=Cynthia|date=2020-01-09|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Films===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Note\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''My Big Fat Hispanic Family''\n| Lele\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Insane Kids''\n| Lele\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''The Walking Dead: No Man's Land''\n| Lele\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Space Between Us (film)|The Space Between Us]]''\n| Tulsa's classmates\n| Cameo\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Caught the Series''\n| Clean up man\n| Guest star\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Scooby Doo Is Back ''\n| Daphne\n| Short film\n|-\n|2017\n|''Latino Hunger Games''\n|Herself\n|Short film\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Airplane Mode (2019 film)|Airplane Mode]]''\n| Herself\n| Main role\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Note\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''We Love You''\n|Callie\n| TV film\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Scream (TV series)|Scream]]''\n| Leah\n| Episode: \"I Know What You Did Last Summer\"\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Escape the Night]]''\n| The Hustler\n| Main role (season 1)\n|-\n|2018\n| ''[[La Voz M\u00e9xico]]''\n| Leading\n| FOX EST\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Artist(s)\n!Role\n|-\n|2016\n| \"[[She's Out of Her Mind]]\"\n| [[Blink-182]]\n| Runner\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2017\n| \"[[Joytime|Summer]]\"\n| [[Marshmello]]\n| Do