{"title_page": "The Sapphires (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2012 film directed by Wayne Blair}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name  = The Sapphires\n| image = The_Sapphires_poster.jpg\n| image_size = 220px\n| border = yes\n| alt = Four woman in sparkling blue dresses, a smiling man with a mustache wearing a red dinner, stands behind them. \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Wayne Blair]]\n| producer = [[Rosemary Blight]]<br />Kylie Du Fresne\n| screenplay = Keith Thompson<br />[[Tony Briggs]]\n| based on = {{Based on|''[[The Sapphires (play)|The Sapphires]]''|Tony Briggs}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Chris O'Dowd]]\n* [[Deborah Mailman]]\n* [[Jessica Mauboy]]\n* [[Shari Sebbens]]\n* [[Miranda Tapsell]]\n* [[Tory Kittles]]\n* [[Eka Darville]]\n}}\n| music = [[Cezary Skubiszewski]]\n| cinematography = [[Warwick Thornton]]\n| editing = [[Dany Cooper]]\n| studio = [[Goalpost Pictures]]\n| distributor = Hopscotch Films {{small|(Australia)}}<br />[[The Weinstein Company]] {{small|(US)}}\n| released = {{Film date|df=yes|2012|05|19|[[2012 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2012|08|09|Australia|2013|03|22|United States}}\n| runtime = 103 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 103:04--><ref>{{cite web|title=''THE SAPPHIRES'' (PG)|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/sapphires-2012-0|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=2012-08-07|accessdate=2013-02-24}}</ref>\n| country = Australia\n| language = English\n| budget = $8\u201310 million<ref name=\"smh\">{{cite news |last1=Maddox |first1=Gary | title=Sapphires proves an Aussie box office gem | date=13 August 2012 | work=Sydney Morning Herald | url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/sapphires-proves-an-aussie-box-office-gem-20120813-244fm.html |publisher=Fairfax Media |accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref>\n| gross = $20,423,628<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n}}\n'''''The Sapphires''''' is a 2012 Australian [[Musical film|musical]] [[comedy-drama]] film based on the 2004 [[The Sapphires (play)|stage play of the same name]], which is loosely based on a true story.<ref name=\"Sparkle, in any colour\">Usher, Robin (15 November 2004),\n [https://www.webcitation.org/6FJyJafMG \"Sparkle, in any colour\"], ''[[The Age]]''. Archived from [http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/11/12/1100227566726.html the original] on 22 March 2013.</ref> The film is directed by [[Wayne Blair]] and written by Keith Thompson and [[Tony Briggs]], the latter of whom wrote the play.\n\n''The Sapphires'' is about four [[Indigenous Australians|Indigenous Australian]] women, Gail ([[Deborah Mailman]]), Julie ([[Jessica Mauboy]]), Kay ([[Shari Sebbens]]) and Cynthia ([[Miranda Tapsell]]), who are discovered by a down on his luck musician ([[Chris O'Dowd]]), and form a music group named The Sapphires, travelling to [[Vietnam]] in 1968 to sing for troops during the [[1968 in the Vietnam War|war]]. Production began in 2010, with the casting of the four members of The Sapphires and filming taking place in and around [[Albury]] in [[Australia]] and [[Vietnam]] during August and September 2011.\n\n''The Sapphires'' made its [[Film premiere|world premiere]] at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]] on 19 May 2012 during its out-of-competition screenings, was theatrically released in Australia on 9 August and received a limited release in the United States on 22 March 2013.\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1968 Australia, Gail and Cynthia head into town to sing country & western songs for a talent contest but their young sister, Julie, is forbidden from going because she has a child and is too young until she bribes a fellow neighbour to take her into town. An alcoholic, Irish talent scout, Dave Lovelace, is scolded by his boss for being late despite him sleeping in his car that is near work. Despite being the best act in the contest, the girls not only do not win, but are told to leave. Dave recognizes their talent and discovers that the troops need singers for Vietnam. Soon, Dave goes to make a call and he says they have been granted a spot to audition in Melbourne. Back at their place, Gail, Cynthia and Julie's mother tells him he can take them but without Julie, until Julie's father tells him not to worry about her. Advised by their grandmother, they meet up with their cousin Kay, who had been living in Melbourne for 10 years after the government took her from her family during the stolen generations, because she was half white. She rejects the offer of joining them, but later changes her mind and meets up at their uncle's place. After days of practising their moves, they are almost ready until Julie gives Cynthia a letter from her fianc\u00e9 that he is going to call it off. Despite that, they manage to audition very well and Kay comes up with the group's name, The Sapphires, after looking at Cynthia's engagement ring.\n\nThe Sapphires are a success with the crowds, but infighting among the women threatens to tear the group apart: Gail acts as the group's aggressive matriarch. Kay struggles with her multi-ethnic identity because 10 years earlier she was taken away from the family by the Government, along with thousands of other fairer-skinned Aboriginal children and sent to live in institutions where they were to be raised 'white'. Julie proves to be the group's best voice with a shot at a singing career. Dave and Gail begin a romance, but his reckless behaviour and a personal secret push Gail's patience to the limit.\n\nWhen The Sapphires do another gig, Cynthia drinks with some of the men and is not allowed to go on again. Later, Dave and Gail talk a little before Dave hands her a letter, telling her to open it later and are about to kiss when they are caught in the crossfire of war; Dave disappears in the chaos and gets shot. The girls manage to escape in a helicopter. At home, Gail reads Dave's letter and realizes he wanted to propose to her, but it was her choice. The women band together and finish their tour. Dave survives and Gail is reunited with him in a Vietnam hospital. The Sapphires return to Australia and Gail and Dave announce to the family that they plan to marry. The Sapphires give a joyous performance for their friends and family in the yard of their home.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Chris O'Dowd]] as Dave Lovelace\n* [[Deborah Mailman]] as Gail\n** Tanika Lonesborough as Young Gail\n* [[Jessica Mauboy]] as Julie\n** Miah Madden as Young Julie\n* [[Shari Sebbens]] as Kay\n** Nioka Brennan as Young Kay\n* [[Miranda Tapsell]] as Cynthia\n** Ava Jean Miller-Porter as Young Cynthia\n* Don Battee as Myron\n* [[Tory Kittles]] as Robby\n* [[Eka Darville]] as Hendo\n* [[Kylie Belling]] as Geraldine\n* [[Judith Lucy]] as Merle\n* [[Georgina Haig]] as Glynis\n* [[Rhys Muldoon]] as Uncle Ed\n* [[Barry Southgate]] and A. Spencer Davis as Two Singing Sailors\n* [[Meyne Wyatt]] as Jimmy Middleton\n** Carlin Briggs as Young Jimmy\n* [[Beau Brady]] as a Marine Sergeant\n\n==The true story==\nThere had been an all-female Australian Aboriginal singing group named The Sapphires in the 1960s, although originally there were three of them: Laurel Robinson (the mother of screenwriter Tony Briggs), Beverly Briggs, and Naomi Mayers. They performed at hotels, pubs, cabarets, clubs, parties, army barracks and universities around Melbourne.<ref name=\"The Sapphires: where are they now?\">Nunn, Gary (5 September 2012)[https://www.webcitation.org/6FfVjcNBG The Sapphires: where are they now?].''[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]''. Archived from [http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/journal/in-conversation-with-the-real-sapphires-movie.htm the original] on 6 April 2013.</ref><ref name=\"var1\" /> When they were invited to Vietnam to perform for the troops, Briggs and Mayers declined, as they were against the war, so Robinson enlisted her sister Lois Peeler to join her.<ref name=\"The Sapphires: where are they now?\"/> In Vietnam, the duo of Robinson and Peeler performed [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]] for a [[New Zealand]] [[M\u0101ori people|Maori]] band they had performed within Melbourne.<ref name=\"Sparkle, in any colour\"/><ref name=\"Maori-Mentored, Soul-Singing Mom Inspired 'The Sapphires'\">[https://www.webcitation.org/6FfalooWj Maori-Mentored, Soul-Singing Mom Inspired 'The Sapphires'].opb.org. 23 March 2013. Archived from [http://www.opb.org/artsandlife/article/npr-maori-mentored-soul-singing-mom-inspired-the-sapphires/ the original] on 24 March 2013.</ref> It was this Maori band who introduced them to soul music; the character of Dave Lovelace, portrayed in the film by Chris O'Dowd, did not exist.<ref name=\" Maori-Mentored, Soul-Singing Mom Inspired 'The Sapphires'\"/> Director Wayne Blair, talking about the creation of the Lovelace character, said \"That's where we went a bit [[Argo (2012 film)|'' Argo'']]\".<ref>Caro, Mark (6 April 2013)[https://www.webcitation.org/6FfV4rKwq Australian film 'The Sapphires' finds its American soul].''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Archived from [http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2013/04/03/3959046/australian-film-the-sapphires.html the original] on 6 April 2013.</ref> Tony Briggs said in an interview in ''[[The Age]]'' in 2004 \"he found it liberating as a writer to expand the number of characters\" as it made the dynamics of the story richer.<ref name=\"Sparkle, in any colour\"/>\n\n==Production==\nBased on [[Tony Briggs]]' 2004 [[The Sapphires (play)|play of the same name]] commissioned by and debuted at [[Melbourne Theatre Company]], the film was first announced in June 2010.<ref name=\"var1\">{{cite news|author=Paul Chai |url= http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118020119 |title='Sapphires' to shine on the bigscreen |work=Variety |date=2 June 2010 |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> The screenplay was co-written by Briggs and Keith Thompson. [[Principal photography|Filming]] primarily took place in [[New South Wales]], at [[Albury]], (and its surrounding towns [[Corowa]], [[Howlong]], [[Culcairn]], [[Henty, New South Wales|Henty]] and [[Morven, New South Wales|Morven]]), with additional shooting taking place in [[Windsor, New South Wales|Windsor]], [[Camden, New South Wales|Camden]], [[Summer Hill, New South Wales|Summerhill]], [[Newtown, New South Wales|Newtown]], and Canal Road Studios in [[Leichhardt, New South Wales|Leichhardt]], between August and September 2011.<ref name=\"gov\">{{cite web|title=The Sapphires|work=[[Parliament of New South Wales]] | url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hansart.nsf/V3Key/LA20110907033|publisher=[[Government of New South Wales]] |accessdate=28 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"dailytelau\">{{cite news |last1=JMo |first1= |last2=Elle |first2=| title=Jessica Mauboy's role in The Sapphires is a real gem | date=11 September 2011 | work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]] | url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/insider/jessica-mauboys-role-in-the-sapphires-is-a-real-gem/story-e6frewt9-1226133772509 |publisher=News Corporation |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"goalpost\">{{cite news |last= |first= | title=The Sapphires | date=27 September 2011 | work=[[Goalpost Pictures]] | url= http://goalpostpictures.com/news/ |publisher=Goalpost Pictures Australia Pty Ltd |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> The rest of the film's production was moved to Vietnam, for a limited shoot.<ref name=\"goalpost\" />\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:Deborah Mailman.jpg|right|thumb|upright|[[Deborah Mailman]], who played Cynthia McCrae in the original 2004 play, stars as Gail McCrae in the film.]]\nOn 2 June 2010, a [[press release]] announced that an open [[casting call]] had begun for ''The Sapphires'', and that Goalpost Pictures Australia were searching for \"four young Indigenous women, aged 16\u201328, to play the leading roles of the four members of [the title singing group]\".<ref name=\"if\">{{cite news|author= |url=http://if.com.au/2010/06/02/article/JLIXZKZWMX.html |title=New film is searching for the Sapphires |work=Inside Film |date=2 June 2010 |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> The audition process involved submitting an audition tape to the casting website by 31 July 2010.<ref name=\"if\" /> Australian singer [[Casey Donovan (singer)|Casey Donovan]], who had starred as Cynthia McCrae in the musical's 2010 production, auditioned for that part, but was unsuccessful, with the role instead going to newcomer Miranda Tapsell.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= | title=Casey Donovan's omission from a film version of show The Sapphires | date=30 July 2011 | work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]] | url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/casey-donovans-omission-from-a-film-version-of-show-the-sapphires/story-e6frewz0-1226104545003 |publisher=News Corporation |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> [[Deborah Mailman]], who also starred as Cynthia in the original 2004 production of the musical, landed the role of Gail McCrae, and [[Jessica Mauboy]] joined the film, being cast as Gail's sister Julie.<ref name=\"creative\">{{cite web|title=The Sapphires (Wayne Blair)|work=Creative Spirits | url= http://www.creativespirits.info/resources/movies/the-sapphires#ixzz1rcIDDiTA | publisher=(Jens Korff) |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Peter H. Kemp |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117925637 |title=The Sapphires (Variety review) |work=Variety |date=28 November 2004 |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Moran |first=Jonathon |title=Mauboy's new tilt at movies |url=http://www.ntnews.com.au/article/2011/06/19/241641_entertainment.html |work=[[Northern Territory News]]|publisher=News Limited|date=19 June 2011 |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> In August 2011, the roles of all four group members were officially announced, when another newcomer, [[Shari Sebbens]], joined the cast as Kay McCrae.<ref name=\"creative\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Moran |first=Jonathon |title=Sapphires dazzle |url=http://www.ntnews.com.au/article/2011/07/17/247711_entertainment.html |work=[[Northern Territory News]]|publisher=News Limited|date=17 July 2011 |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> [[Chris O'Dowd]] was added to the film, playing the role of Dave, who discovers The Sapphires.<ref>{{cite news |last=|first= | title=Chris O'Dowd joins the cast of The Sapphires | date=15 August 2011 | work=Goalpost Pictures | url=http://goalpostpictures.com/news/ |publisher=Goalpost Pictures Australia Pty Ltd |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{main|The Sapphires: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack}}\n[[File:Jessica Mauboy at Mbantua Festival.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Mauboy performing \"[[Ngarra Burra Ferra]]\" at the 2013 Mbantua Festival in [[Alice Springs, Northern Territory]] with [[Aboriginal Australian]] students from Yipirinya State Primary School, of which Mauboy is the official ambassador.]]\nThe original [[soundtrack]] was released on 27 July 2012 by [[Sony Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jbhifionline.com.au/music/soundtracks/sapphires-the-ost/668693|title=Sapphires, The \u2013 Ost|work=[[JB Hi-Fi]]|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref> It features the vocals of [[Jessica Mauboy]], [[Jade MacRae]], [[Lou Bennett (musician)|Lou Bennett]], Juanita Tippens and Darren Percival, with Mauboy singing in ten of the sixteen songs.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first= |title=Jessica Mauboy has gotcha call |url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/entertainment/jess-has-gotcha-call/story-e6fredpu-1226420077911 |work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|publisher=News Limited (News Corporation)|date=8 July 2012 |accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref> An original track called \"Gotcha\", co-written by Mauboy, [[Ilan Kidron]], and Louis Schoorl, was released as a single on 13 July.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bub |first=Adam |title=Watch: Jessica Mauboy gets sexy on the set of new clip 'Gotcha'|url=http://music.ninemsn.com.au/blog.aspx?blogentryid=1026135&showcomments=true |work=[[Ninemsn]]|publisher=[[Nine Entertainment Co.]] ([[Microsoft]])|date=12 July 2012 |accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.filmink.com.au/filmbiz/notice/5869/ |title='The Sapphires' Soundtrack To Release July 27 |magazine=[[Filmink]] |accessdate=17 July 2012|date=3 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/gotcha-single/id543205715  |title='Gotcha' \u2013 Single \u2013 Jessica Mauboy |publisher=[[iTunes Store]]. [[Apple Inc]] |accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref> Two weeks after its chart debut, ''The Sapphires'' soundtrack hit number one on the ARIA Album Chart and the ARIA Australian Albums Chart.\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its [[Film premiere|world premiere]] on 19 May at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]], at the midnight out-of-competition screening.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sandy George |url=http://if.com.au/2012/05/01/article/The-Sapphires-gets-gala-midnight-screening-at-Cannes/TKTTVKGTYS.html |title=The Sapphires gets gala midnight screening at Cannes |work=Inside Film |date=1 May 2012 |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> Following the premiere, the audience in attendance gave the cast and crew a ten-minute standing ovation.<ref>{{cite news | title=A big night for ... Sapphires to sparkle|date=21 May 2012 | work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] | url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/the-diary/a-big-night-for--sapphires-to-sparkle-20120520-1yz37.html |first1=Matt |last1=Buchanan|first2=Scott |last2=Ellis | accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bodey |first=Michael | title=Sapphires proves a gem as it steals the show at Cannes | date=21 May 2012 | work=The Australian | url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/film/sapphires-proves-a-gem-as-it-steals-the-show-at-cannes/story-e6frg8pf-1226361649633 |publisher=News Limited (News Corporation) |accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Roger Friedman |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/rogerfriedman/2012/05/19/cannes-the-sapphires-gets-a-huge-standing-o-diana-ross-may-attend-tomorrows-screening/ |title=Cannes: 'The Sapphires' Gets a Huge Standing O, Diana Ross May Attend Tomorrow's Screening |work=Forbes |date=19 May 2012 |accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> It premiered in Australia at the [[Melbourne International Film Festival]] on 2 August, with its cinematic release on 9 August, distributed by Hopscotch Films.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Sapphires to screen in Official Selection at Cannes|work=[[Screen Australia]] | url=http://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/news_and_events/Media-Release-documents/2012/mr_120430_Cannes_Sapphires.pdf |publisher=[[Australian Government]] | date= 30 April 2012| accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bodey |first=Michael | title=Sapphires to adorn international settings | date=16 May 2012 | work=[[The Australian]] | url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/sapphires-to-adorn-international-settings/story-e6frg8n6-1226356642151 |publisher=News Limited (News Corporation) |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> [[Entertainment One]] handled distribution in the United Kingdom, Ireland, and Canada, while [[ZON Lusomundo|Lusomundo]], Diaphana, and Lev Films released the film in Portugal, France, and [[Israel]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news|author=Brendan Swift |url=http://if.com.au/2012/02/17/article/ZGKNDXSMKU.html |title=The Sapphires, starring Chris O'Dowd and Jessica Mauboy, sold to Canada, France |work=Inside Film |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> [[The Weinstein Company]] bought the rights to distribute the film in the United States and other countries.<ref>{{cite news | title=Australian film The Sapphires backed by The Weinstein Company ahead of Cannes Film Festival premiere |date=16 May 2012 | work=[[Herald Sun]] |publisher=[[The Herald and Weekly Times]] (News Corporation) | url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/movies/australian-film-the-sapphires-backed-by-the-weinstein-company-ahead-of-cannes-film-festival-premiere/story-e6frf9h6-1226357891403 |first=Neala |last=Johnson | accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n{{Anchor|DVD release|DVD|Bluray}} \nThe US release of the DVD attracted controversy as the result of the design for the DVD's cover. The artwork placed actor Chris O'Dowd prominently in the foreground, with the four female stars appearing in the background and coloured with a blue wash. The decision was described as both sexist and racist, with O'Dowd describing the decision as \"ill-judged, insensitive and everything the film wasn't\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BigBoyler/status/363093898320556032 |title=chris o'dowd on Twitter: \"@billwhatonair it's ridiculous, it's misleading, it's ill-judged, insensitive and everything the film wasn't.\" |publisher=Twitter |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | date = 6 August 2013 | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-23586169 | work = [[BBC News]] | title = Sapphires DVD complaint over O'Dowd image prompts apology }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Douglas |first= Tim. | date = 2 August 2013 | url = http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/film/the-sapphires-us-dvd-cover-vile-says-chris-odowd/story-e6frg8pf-1226690262756 | title = The Sapphires US DVD cover 'vile', says Chris O'Dowd | work = [[The Australian]] | accessdate = 3 August 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Lu | first = Ann | date = 3 August 2013 | url = http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/496465/20130803/sapphires-dvd-cover-art-racist-sexist-deborah.htm | title = U.S. DVD Cover Of Aussie Film 'The Sapphires' Called 'Sexist' And 'Racist' | work = [[International Business Times]] | accessdate = 3 August 2013 }}</ref>\nAnchor Bay expressed regret for any \"unintentional upset caused\" and said different artwork was being considered for future orders.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/05/the-sapphires-dvd-racist_n_3709074.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Mallika | last=Rao | title=Is This DVD Cover Racist? | date=5 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\nIn Australia, the film was the highest-earning Australian film on its opening weekend, grossing $2,320,000 from 275 cinemas.<ref name=\"smh\" /> [[News.com.au]] said it was the strongest first weekend for an Australian-made film since ''[[Tomorrow, When the War Began (film)|Tomorrow, When the War Began]]'', which earned $3,860,000 upon its 2010 release.<ref name=\"newscomau\">{{cite news | title=The Sapphires a box office smash hit on opening weekend |date=13 August 2012 | work=[[News.com.au]] |publisher=[[News Limited]] (News Corporation) | url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/movies/the-sapphires-a-box-office-smash-hit-on-opening-weekend/story-e6frfmvr-1226449423305 |first=Neala |last=Johnson | accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref> As of 31 October 2012, the film had grossed AU$14,215,596 at the Australian box office.<ref name=\"urbancinefile.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.urbancinefile.com.au/home/boxoffice.asp |title=Box Office |publisher=Urban Cinefile |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref>\n\nThe film was far less successful in international markets than in its Australian release, with roughly $5 million from all international releases combined versus over $14 million in its Australian release alone.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=sapphires.htm | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | publisher= Amazon.com|title=The Sapphires (2013) - International Box Office Results}}</ref>\n\nIn France, the film opened at #13 with just 35,786 admissions from 162 screens over its first week (25,847 over five days).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allocine.fr/boxoffice/boxofficedetail_gen_pays=5001.html?date=2012-08-08 |title=Box Office Cin\u00e9ma France - AlloCin\u00e9 |website=Allocine.fr |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> It was dubbed \"Le Flop\" by French box office website Le Box Office Pour Les Nuls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leboxofficepourlesnuls.com/2012/08/14/lundi-13-aout-2012-les-chiffres-cles-du-box-office/ |title=LUNDI 13 AOUT 2012 : LES CHIFFRES CLES DU BOX-OFFICE |publisher=Le box-office pour les nuls |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> In its first major English-language opening outside of Australia, the UK, the film opened at #7 and to a little under 25% of the box office it earned in its Australian opening weekend, on a roughly similar number of screens (279 vs. 233). The film exited UK cinemas after just 5 weeks in release with a final box office take of \u00a3680,643, equivalent to around AU$1m. The UK final box office takings were less than 1/14 of the film's Australian final box office takings.<ref name=\"mojo-uk\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/intl/uk/?yr=2012&wk=49&p.htm|title=United Kingdom Box Office|date=2012-12-19|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> In its United States release, where the film only appeared in the top 20 for one weekend (at #19, 5\u20137 April 2013), the film completed its run with just under $2.5m, and releases in Germany and the Netherlands yielded under $100,000 each.<ref name=\"mojo-intl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=sapphires.htm |accessdate=20 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513111758/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=sapphires.htm |title=The Sapphires|archivedate=13 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n<!-- critical overview -->\n''The Sapphires'' received positive reviews from Cannes, dubbed as the Australian version of ''[[Dreamgirls (film)|Dreamgirls]]'' (2006), another film based on a play about a '60s girl group.<ref>{{cite news | title=Cannes unveils an unexpected gem (+trailer) |date=24 May 2012 | work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |publisher=[[APN News & Media]] | url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=10807651 |first=Kerry |last=O'Shea | accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Chris O'Dowd's 'The Sapphires' receives rave reviews at Cannes Film Festival \u2013 VIDEO|date=21 May 2012 | work=IrishCentral |publisher= | url= http://www.irishcentral.com/ent/Chris-ODowds-The-Sapphires-receives-rave-reviews-at-Cannes-Film-Festival-152268075.html |first=Jake |last=Coyle | accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a score of 91% based on reviews from 131 critics; their average rating was calculated as 6.9/10.<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{cite web|url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_sapphires_2012/|title = The Sapphires Movie Reviews, Pictures|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=5 October 2012}}</ref> Metacritic gives the film a \"generally positive\" rating of 67% based on reviews from 30 critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-sapphires |title=The Sapphires Reviews |website=Metacritic |date=2013-03-19 |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref>\n\n<!-- International critics -->\nGuy Lodge from ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' said [[Chris O'Dowd]]'s \"dorky-dirty warmth and manic performance energy... keeps the proceedings bouncy even when the script loses its own fizz.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Guy Lodge |url= http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117947584/ |title=Variety Reviews \u2013 The Sapphires |work=Variety |date=20 May 2012 |accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref> \nMark Adams of ''[[Screen International]]'' called O'Dowd an \"increasingly charismatic screen presence\" who \"helps give the film an edginess, spontaneity and some real laugh-out-loud moments.\"<ref>{{cite news | title=The Sapphires \u2013 Review |date=21 May 2012 | work=[[Screen International]] |publisher=[[EMAP|Emap International Limited]] | url= http://www.screendaily.com/reviews/the-latest/the-sapphires/5042342.article |first=Mark |last=Adams | accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref>\nEric Kohn from [[IndieWire]] gave it a C-, believing that it \"belongs on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] more than the big screen\".<ref>{{cite news |last =Kohn |first =Eric | title = CANNES REVIEW: Why Cannes Breakout 'The Sapphires' Belongs On Broadway More Than the Big Screen | work = [[IndieWire]] | date = 21 May 2012 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/cannes-review-why-cannes-breakout-the-sapphires-belongs-on-broadway-more-than-the-big-screen | accessdate =17 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\nHenry Barnes of ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave the film three stars out of five, calling it \"a sweet 'n' dumb feelgood bopper.\"<ref>{{cite news | title=Cannes 2012: The Sapphires \u2013 review |date=21 May 2012 | work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] | url= https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/may/21/the-sapphires-review?newsfeed=true |first=Henry |last=Barnes | accessdate=28 May 2012 | location=London}}</ref> \nBrad Brevet of ''Rope of Silicon'' gave it a B-, summing it up as, \"good music, good performances and good fun and should play well across several demographic quadrants.\"<ref>{{cite news |last =Brevet |first =Brad | title = 'The Sapphires' Movie Review \u2013 2012 Cannes Film Festival | work = Rope of Silicon | date = 21 May 2012 | url = http://www.ropeofsilicon.com/sapphires-movie-review-2012-cannes-film-festival/ | accessdate =28 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\n[[Robbie Collin]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' gave the \"workaday Australian comedy\" three stars, calling it \"uncomplicated\" but praising Chris O'Dowd for elevating every scene he is in.<ref>{{cite news | title=Cannes 2012: The Hunt/ Beyond The Hills / The Sapphires, review |date=21 May 2012 | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] | url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/cannes-film-festival/9279361/Cannes-2012-The-Hunt-Beyond-The-Hills-The-Sapphires-review.html |first=Robbie |last=Collin | accessdate=17 July 2012 | location=London}}</ref> \nRoss Miller of ''Thoughts On Film'' gave the film three stars, saying that it \"may not break any especially new ground or end up in a place you're not expecting but along the way it's a genuinely pleasant watch.\"<ref>{{cite news | title=Movie Review: The Sapphires |date=30 October 2012 | work=Thoughts On Film|publisher=Thoughts On Film| url= http://thoughtsonfilm.co.uk/movie-reviews/the-sapphires-movie-review/ |first=Ross |last=Miller | accessdate=2 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Australian critics -->\nFiona Williams of [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]] awarded the film three-and-a-half stars out of five, commenting that \"There's much to love, lots to like... and enough roof-lifting musical numbers to make up for the dodgy bits.\"<ref>{{cite news | title=The Sapphires (review) |date=| work=[[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]] |publisher= | url= http://www.sbs.com.au/films/movie/13488/the-sapphires |first=Fiona |last=Williams | accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nAcademic Bruno Starrs makes the argument that the film's Aboriginal protagonists undergo a journey in which they learn the importance of choosing the protest songs of black Soul over the white coloniser's \"whining\" Country and Western songs. Their song choices are an assertion of Indigenous sovereignty and Starrs argues that the Aboriginal Australian 'Welcome to Country' is twice subverted to reinforce this theme, firstly in the Cummeragunja pub and secondly in war-torn Vietnam.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eprints.qut.edu.au/75050/ |title=Sovereignty, song and 'The Sapphires' (Wayne Blair 2012) &#124; QUT ePrints |website=Eprints.qut.edu.au |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{Anchor|Accolades|Awards}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Ceremony\n! Category\n! Recipient\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[AWGIE Awards|45th AWGIE Awards]]<ref>{{cite news | title=The Sapphires and Not Suitable For Children top AWGIE Awards |date=27 August 2012 | work=Inside Film |publisher= | url=http://if.com.au/2012/08/27/article/The-Sapphires-and-Not-Suitable-For-Children-top-AWGIE-Awards/APOYDDBIPU.html |first=Anthony |last=Soegito | accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref>\n| Best Feature Film (screenplay) \u2013 Adaptation\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Keith Thompson<br>[[Tony Briggs]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|[[Major AWGIE Award|Most Outstanding Script of 2012]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[ARIA Music Awards of 2012|26th ARIA Music Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history/year/2012|title=2012 ARIA Awards Winners By Year |publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) |accessdate=7 October 2012 }}</ref>\n| [[ARIA Award for Best Original Soundtrack, Cast or Show Album|Best Original Soundtrack/Cast/Show Album]]\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Chicago International Film Festival|48th Chicago International Film Festival]]\n| Gold Hugo for Best Feature\n|rowspan=2|[[Wayne Blair]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Denver Film Festival|35th Denver Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Cangialosi|first=Jason|title=35th Starz Denver Film Festival Award Winners|url=http://www.milehighcinema.com/2012/11/15/35th-starz-denver-film-festival-award-winners/|publisher=Mile High Cinema|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref>\n| People's Choice Award for Best Narrative Feature\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"17\" | [[AACTA Awards]]<ref>{{cite news | title=The Sapphires top of the AACTAs with 12 nominations |date=3 December 2012 | work=[[Herald Sun]] |publisher=[[The Herald and Weekly Times]] (News Corporation) | url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/aacta-award-nominations/story-e6frf96f-1226529040189 |first1=Vicky |last1=Roach|first2=Holly |last2=Byrnes | accessdate=8 December 2012}}</ref><br><small>([[2nd AACTA Awards|2nd]])</small>\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n| [[Rosemary Blight]], Kylie du Fresne\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]\n| Wayne Blair\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[AACTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n| Keith Thompson\n|{{won}}\n|-\n| Tony Briggs\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Lead Actor]]\n| [[Chris O'Dowd]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Lead Actress]]\n| [[Deborah Mailman]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| [[Jessica Mauboy]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| [[Warwick Thornton]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n| [[Dany Cooper]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=5|[[AACTA Award for Best Sound|Best Sound]]\n| Andrew Plain\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Bry Jones\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Pete Smith\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Ben Osmo\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| John Simpson\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]]\n| Melinda Doring\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]]\n| Tess Schofield\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]]\n| James Rogers\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Deadly Awards 2013]]<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-09-11/abc-among-those-honoured-in-2013-deadly-awards/4949856 Aboriginal magistrate Pat O'Shane, Archie Roach honoured at Deadly Awards], ''ABC News'', 11 September 2013.</ref>\n|colspan=2|Film of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb title|1673697|The Sapphires}}\n* {{mojo title|sapphires|The Sapphires}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|the_sapphires_2012|The Sapphires}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-sapphires|The Sapphires}}\n\n{{AACTA Award Best Film 2010\u20132029}}\n{{Films and television series about Indigenous Australia |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sapphires, The}}\n[[Category:2012 films]]\n[[Category:2010s musical comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Australian films]]\n[[Category:Australian comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Australian musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Australian biographical films]]\n[[Category:Biographical musicals]]\n[[Category:Films about music and musicians]]\n[[Category:Films set in Australia]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1960s]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1968]]\n[[Category:Films set in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian independent films]]\n[[Category:Vietnam War films]]\n[[Category:Australian films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films about Aboriginal Australians]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Cezary Skubiszewski]]\n[[Category:2012 independent films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Australian women]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2012 film directed by Wayne Blair}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name  = The Sapphires\n| image = The_Sapphires_poster.jpg\n| image_size = 220px\n| border = yes\n| alt = Four woman in sparkling blue dresses, a smiling man with a mustache wearing a red dinner, stands behind them. \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Wayne Blair]]\n| producer = [[Rosemary Blight]]<br />Kylie Du Fresne\n| screenplay = Keith Thompson<br />[[Tony Briggs]]\n| based on = {{Based on|''[[The Sapphires (play)|The Sapphires]]''|Tony Briggs}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Chris O'Dowd]]\n* [[Deborah Mailman]]\n* [[Jessica Mauboy]]\n* [[Shari Sebbens]]\n* [[Miranda Tapsell]]\n* [[Tory Kittles]]\n* [[Eka Darville]]\n}}\n| music = [[Cezary Skubiszewski]]\n| cinematography = [[Warwick Thornton]]\n| editing = [[Dany Cooper]]\n| studio = [[Goalpost Pictures]]\n| distributor = Hopscotch Films {{small|(Australia)}}<br />[[The Weinstein Company]] {{small|(US)}}\n| released = {{Film date|df=yes|2012|05|19|[[2012 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2012|08|09|Australia|2013|03|22|United States}}\n| runtime = 103 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 103:04--><ref>{{cite web|title=''THE SAPPHIRES'' (PG)|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/sapphires-2012-0|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=2012-08-07|accessdate=2013-02-24}}</ref>\n| country = Australia\n| language = English\n| budget = $8\u201310 million<ref name=\"smh\">{{cite news |last1=Maddox |first1=Gary | title=Sapphires proves an Aussie box office gem | date=13 August 2012 | work=Sydney Morning Herald | url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/sapphires-proves-an-aussie-box-office-gem-20120813-244fm.html |publisher=Fairfax Media |accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref>\n| gross = $20,423,628<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n}}\n'''''The Sapphires''''' is a 2012 Australian [[Musical film|musical]] [[comedy-drama]] film based on the 2004 [[The Sapphires (play)|stage play of the same name]], which is loosely based on a true story.<ref name=\"Sparkle, in any colour\">Usher, Robin (15 November 2004),\n [https://www.webcitation.org/6FJyJafMG \"Sparkle, in any colour\"], ''[[The Age]]''. Archived from [http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/11/12/1100227566726.html the original] on 22 March 2013.</ref> The film is directed by [[Wayne Blair]] and written by Keith Thompson and [[Tony Briggs]], the latter of whom wrote the play.\n\n''The Sapphires'' is about four [[Indigenous Australians|Indigenous Australian]] women, Gail ([[Deborah Mailman]]), Julie ([[Jessica Mauboy]]), Kay ([[Shari Sebbens]]) and Cynthia ([[Miranda Tapsell]]), who are discovered by a talent scout ([[Chris O'Dowd]]), and form a music group named The Sapphires, travelling to [[Vietnam]] in 1968 to sing for troops during the [[1968 in the Vietnam War|war]]. Production began in 2010, with the casting of the four members of The Sapphires and filming taking place in and around [[Albury]] in [[Australia]] and [[Vietnam]] during August and September 2011.\n\n''The Sapphires'' made its [[Film premiere|world premiere]] at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]] on 19 May 2012 during its out-of-competition screenings, was theatrically released in Australia on 9 August and received a limited release in the United States on 22 March 2013.\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1968 Australia, Gail and Cynthia head into town to sing country & western songs for a talent contest but their young sister, Julie, is forbidden from going because she has a child and is too young until she bribes a fellow neighbour to take her into town. An alcoholic, Irish talent scout, Dave Lovelace, is scolded by his boss for being late despite him sleeping in his car that is near work. Despite being the best act in the contest, the girls not only do not win, but are told to leave. Dave recognizes their talent and discovers that the troops need singers for Vietnam. Soon, Dave goes to make a call and he says they have been granted a spot to audition in Melbourne. Back at their place, Gail, Cynthia and Julie's mother tells him he can take them but without Julie, until Julie's father tells him not to worry about her. Advised by their grandmother, they meet up with their cousin Kay, who had been living in Melbourne for 10 years after the government took her from her family during the stolen generations, because she was half white. She rejects the offer of joining them, but later changes her mind and meets up at their uncle's place. After days of practising their moves, they are almost ready until Julie gives Cynthia a letter from her fianc\u00e9 that he is going to call it off. Despite that, they manage to audition very well and Kay comes up with the group's name, The Sapphires, after looking at Cynthia's engagement ring.\n\nThe Sapphires are a success with the crowds, but infighting among the women threatens to tear the group apart: Gail acts as the group's aggressive matriarch. Kay struggles with her multi-ethnic identity because 10 years earlier she was taken away from the family by the Government, along with thousands of other fairer-skinned Aboriginal children and sent to live in institutions where they were to be raised 'white'. Julie proves to be the group's best voice with a shot at a singing career. Dave and Gail begin a romance, but his reckless behaviour and a personal secret push Gail's patience to the limit.\n\nWhen The Sapphires do another gig, Cynthia drinks with some of the men and is not allowed to go on again. Later, Dave and Gail talk a little before Dave hands her a letter, telling her to open it later and are about to kiss when they are caught in the crossfire of war; Dave disappears in the chaos and gets shot. The girls manage to escape in a helicopter. At home, Gail reads Dave's letter and realizes he wanted to propose to her, but it was her choice. The women band together and finish their tour. Dave survives and Gail is reunited with him in a Vietnam hospital. The Sapphires return to Australia and Gail and Dave announce to the family that they plan to marry. The Sapphires give a joyous performance for their friends and family in the yard of their home.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Chris O'Dowd]] as Dave Lovelace\n* [[Deborah Mailman]] as Gail\n** Tanika Lonesborough as Young Gail\n* [[Jessica Mauboy]] as Julie\n** Miah Madden as Young Julie\n* [[Shari Sebbens]] as Kay\n** Nioka Brennan as Young Kay\n* [[Miranda Tapsell]] as Cynthia\n** Ava Jean Miller-Porter as Young Cynthia\n* Don Battee as Myron\n* [[Tory Kittles]] as Robby\n* [[Eka Darville]] as Hendo\n* [[Kylie Belling]] as Geraldine\n* [[Judith Lucy]] as Merle\n* [[Georgina Haig]] as Glynis\n* [[Rhys Muldoon]] as Uncle Ed\n* [[Barry Southgate]] and A. Spencer Davis as Two Singing Sailors\n* [[Meyne Wyatt]] as Jimmy Middleton\n** Carlin Briggs as Young Jimmy\n* [[Beau Brady]] as a Marine Sergeant\n\n==The true story==\nThere had been an all-female Australian Aboriginal singing group named The Sapphires in the 1960s, although originally there were three of them: Laurel Robinson (the mother of screenwriter Tony Briggs), Beverly Briggs, and Naomi Mayers. They performed at hotels, pubs, cabarets, clubs, parties, army barracks and universities around Melbourne.<ref name=\"The Sapphires: where are they now?\">Nunn, Gary (5 September 2012)[https://www.webcitation.org/6FfVjcNBG The Sapphires: where are they now?].''[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]''. Archived from [http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/journal/in-conversation-with-the-real-sapphires-movie.htm the original] on 6 April 2013.</ref><ref name=\"var1\" /> When they were invited to Vietnam to perform for the troops, Briggs and Mayers declined, as they were against the war, so Robinson enlisted her sister Lois Peeler to join her.<ref name=\"The Sapphires: where are they now?\"/> In Vietnam, the duo of Robinson and Peeler performed [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]] for a [[New Zealand]] [[M\u0101ori people|Maori]] band they had performed within Melbourne.<ref name=\"Sparkle, in any colour\"/><ref name=\"Maori-Mentored, Soul-Singing Mom Inspired 'The Sapphires'\">[https://www.webcitation.org/6FfalooWj Maori-Mentored, Soul-Singing Mom Inspired 'The Sapphires'].opb.org. 23 March 2013. Archived from [http://www.opb.org/artsandlife/article/npr-maori-mentored-soul-singing-mom-inspired-the-sapphires/ the original] on 24 March 2013.</ref> It was this Maori band who introduced them to soul music; the character of Dave Lovelace, portrayed in the film by Chris O'Dowd, did not exist.<ref name=\" Maori-Mentored, Soul-Singing Mom Inspired 'The Sapphires'\"/> Director Wayne Blair, talking about the creation of the Lovelace character, said \"That's where we went a bit [[Argo (2012 film)|'' Argo'']]\".<ref>Caro, Mark (6 April 2013)[https://www.webcitation.org/6FfV4rKwq Australian film 'The Sapphires' finds its American soul].''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Archived from [http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2013/04/03/3959046/australian-film-the-sapphires.html the original] on 6 April 2013.</ref> Tony Briggs said in an interview in ''[[The Age]]'' in 2004 \"he found it liberating as a writer to expand the number of characters\" as it made the dynamics of the story richer.<ref name=\"Sparkle, in any colour\"/>\n\n==Production==\nBased on [[Tony Briggs]]' 2004 [[The Sapphires (play)|play of the same name]] commissioned by and debuted at [[Melbourne Theatre Company]], the film was first announced in June 2010.<ref name=\"var1\">{{cite news|author=Paul Chai |url= http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118020119 |title='Sapphires' to shine on the bigscreen |work=Variety |date=2 June 2010 |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> The screenplay was co-written by Briggs and Keith Thompson. [[Principal photography|Filming]] primarily took place in [[New South Wales]], at [[Albury]], (and its surrounding towns [[Corowa]], [[Howlong]], [[Culcairn]], [[Henty, New South Wales|Henty]] and [[Morven, New South Wales|Morven]]), with additional shooting taking place in [[Windsor, New South Wales|Windsor]], [[Camden, New South Wales|Camden]], [[Summer Hill, New South Wales|Summerhill]], [[Newtown, New South Wales|Newtown]], and Canal Road Studios in [[Leichhardt, New South Wales|Leichhardt]], between August and September 2011.<ref name=\"gov\">{{cite web|title=The Sapphires|work=[[Parliament of New South Wales]] | url=http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/hansart.nsf/V3Key/LA20110907033|publisher=[[Government of New South Wales]] |accessdate=28 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"dailytelau\">{{cite news |last1=JMo |first1= |last2=Elle |first2=| title=Jessica Mauboy's role in The Sapphires is a real gem | date=11 September 2011 | work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]] | url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/insider/jessica-mauboys-role-in-the-sapphires-is-a-real-gem/story-e6frewt9-1226133772509 |publisher=News Corporation |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"goalpost\">{{cite news |last= |first= | title=The Sapphires | date=27 September 2011 | work=[[Goalpost Pictures]] | url= http://goalpostpictures.com/news/ |publisher=Goalpost Pictures Australia Pty Ltd |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> The rest of the film's production was moved to Vietnam, for a limited shoot.<ref name=\"goalpost\" />\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:Deborah Mailman.jpg|right|thumb|upright|[[Deborah Mailman]], who played Cynthia McCrae in the original 2004 play, stars as Gail McCrae in the film.]]\nOn 2 June 2010, a [[press release]] announced that an open [[casting call]] had begun for ''The Sapphires'', and that Goalpost Pictures Australia were searching for \"four young Indigenous women, aged 16\u201328, to play the leading roles of the four members of [the title singing group]\".<ref name=\"if\">{{cite news|author= |url=http://if.com.au/2010/06/02/article/JLIXZKZWMX.html |title=New film is searching for the Sapphires |work=Inside Film |date=2 June 2010 |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> The audition process involved submitting an audition tape to the casting website by 31 July 2010.<ref name=\"if\" /> Australian singer [[Casey Donovan (singer)|Casey Donovan]], who had starred as Cynthia McCrae in the musical's 2010 production, auditioned for that part, but was unsuccessful, with the role instead going to newcomer Miranda Tapsell.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= | title=Casey Donovan's omission from a film version of show The Sapphires | date=30 July 2011 | work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]] | url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/casey-donovans-omission-from-a-film-version-of-show-the-sapphires/story-e6frewz0-1226104545003 |publisher=News Corporation |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> [[Deborah Mailman]], who also starred as Cynthia in the original 2004 production of the musical, landed the role of Gail McCrae, and [[Jessica Mauboy]] joined the film, being cast as Gail's sister Julie.<ref name=\"creative\">{{cite web|title=The Sapphires (Wayne Blair)|work=Creative Spirits | url= http://www.creativespirits.info/resources/movies/the-sapphires#ixzz1rcIDDiTA | publisher=(Jens Korff) |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Peter H. Kemp |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117925637 |title=The Sapphires (Variety review) |work=Variety |date=28 November 2004 |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Moran |first=Jonathon |title=Mauboy's new tilt at movies |url=http://www.ntnews.com.au/article/2011/06/19/241641_entertainment.html |work=[[Northern Territory News]]|publisher=News Limited|date=19 June 2011 |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> In August 2011, the roles of all four group members were officially announced, when another newcomer, [[Shari Sebbens]], joined the cast as Kay McCrae.<ref name=\"creative\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Moran |first=Jonathon |title=Sapphires dazzle |url=http://www.ntnews.com.au/article/2011/07/17/247711_entertainment.html |work=[[Northern Territory News]]|publisher=News Limited|date=17 July 2011 |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> [[Chris O'Dowd]] was added to the film, playing the role of Dave, who discovers The Sapphires.<ref>{{cite news |last=|first= | title=Chris O'Dowd joins the cast of The Sapphires | date=15 August 2011 | work=Goalpost Pictures | url=http://goalpostpictures.com/news/ |publisher=Goalpost Pictures Australia Pty Ltd |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{main|The Sapphires: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack}}\n[[File:Jessica Mauboy at Mbantua Festival.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Mauboy performing \"[[Ngarra Burra Ferra]]\" at the 2013 Mbantua Festival in [[Alice Springs, Northern Territory]] with [[Aboriginal Australian]] students from Yipirinya State Primary School, of which Mauboy is the official ambassador.]]\nThe original [[soundtrack]] was released on 27 July 2012 by [[Sony Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jbhifionline.com.au/music/soundtracks/sapphires-the-ost/668693|title=Sapphires, The \u2013 Ost|work=[[JB Hi-Fi]]|publisher=|accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref> It features the vocals of [[Jessica Mauboy]], [[Jade MacRae]], [[Lou Bennett (musician)|Lou Bennett]], Juanita Tippens and Darren Percival, with Mauboy singing in ten of the sixteen songs.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first= |title=Jessica Mauboy has gotcha call |url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/entertainment/jess-has-gotcha-call/story-e6fredpu-1226420077911 |work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|publisher=News Limited (News Corporation)|date=8 July 2012 |accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref> An original track called \"Gotcha\", co-written by Mauboy, [[Ilan Kidron]], and Louis Schoorl, was released as a single on 13 July.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bub |first=Adam |title=Watch: Jessica Mauboy gets sexy on the set of new clip 'Gotcha'|url=http://music.ninemsn.com.au/blog.aspx?blogentryid=1026135&showcomments=true |work=[[Ninemsn]]|publisher=[[Nine Entertainment Co.]] ([[Microsoft]])|date=12 July 2012 |accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.filmink.com.au/filmbiz/notice/5869/ |title='The Sapphires' Soundtrack To Release July 27 |magazine=[[Filmink]] |accessdate=17 July 2012|date=3 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/gotcha-single/id543205715  |title='Gotcha' \u2013 Single \u2013 Jessica Mauboy |publisher=[[iTunes Store]]. [[Apple Inc]] |accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref> Two weeks after its chart debut, ''The Sapphires'' soundtrack hit number one on the ARIA Album Chart and the ARIA Australian Albums Chart.\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its [[Film premiere|world premiere]] on 19 May at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]], at the midnight out-of-competition screening.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sandy George |url=http://if.com.au/2012/05/01/article/The-Sapphires-gets-gala-midnight-screening-at-Cannes/TKTTVKGTYS.html |title=The Sapphires gets gala midnight screening at Cannes |work=Inside Film |date=1 May 2012 |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> Following the premiere, the audience in attendance gave the cast and crew a ten-minute standing ovation.<ref>{{cite news | title=A big night for ... Sapphires to sparkle|date=21 May 2012 | work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] | url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/the-diary/a-big-night-for--sapphires-to-sparkle-20120520-1yz37.html |first1=Matt |last1=Buchanan|first2=Scott |last2=Ellis | accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bodey |first=Michael | title=Sapphires proves a gem as it steals the show at Cannes | date=21 May 2012 | work=The Australian | url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/film/sapphires-proves-a-gem-as-it-steals-the-show-at-cannes/story-e6frg8pf-1226361649633 |publisher=News Limited (News Corporation) |accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Roger Friedman |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/rogerfriedman/2012/05/19/cannes-the-sapphires-gets-a-huge-standing-o-diana-ross-may-attend-tomorrows-screening/ |title=Cannes: 'The Sapphires' Gets a Huge Standing O, Diana Ross May Attend Tomorrow's Screening |work=Forbes |date=19 May 2012 |accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> It premiered in Australia at the [[Melbourne International Film Festival]] on 2 August, with its cinematic release on 9 August, distributed by Hopscotch Films.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Sapphires to screen in Official Selection at Cannes|work=[[Screen Australia]] | url=http://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/news_and_events/Media-Release-documents/2012/mr_120430_Cannes_Sapphires.pdf |publisher=[[Australian Government]] | date= 30 April 2012| accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bodey |first=Michael | title=Sapphires to adorn international settings | date=16 May 2012 | work=[[The Australian]] | url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/sapphires-to-adorn-international-settings/story-e6frg8n6-1226356642151 |publisher=News Limited (News Corporation) |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> [[Entertainment One]] handled distribution in the United Kingdom, Ireland, and Canada, while [[ZON Lusomundo|Lusomundo]], Diaphana, and Lev Films released the film in Portugal, France, and [[Israel]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news|author=Brendan Swift |url=http://if.com.au/2012/02/17/article/ZGKNDXSMKU.html |title=The Sapphires, starring Chris O'Dowd and Jessica Mauboy, sold to Canada, France |work=Inside Film |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> [[The Weinstein Company]] bought the rights to distribute the film in the United States and other countries.<ref>{{cite news | title=Australian film The Sapphires backed by The Weinstein Company ahead of Cannes Film Festival premiere |date=16 May 2012 | work=[[Herald Sun]] |publisher=[[The Herald and Weekly Times]] (News Corporation) | url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/movies/australian-film-the-sapphires-backed-by-the-weinstein-company-ahead-of-cannes-film-festival-premiere/story-e6frf9h6-1226357891403 |first=Neala |last=Johnson | accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n{{Anchor|DVD release|DVD|Bluray}} \nThe US release of the DVD attracted controversy as the result of the design for the DVD's cover. The artwork placed actor Chris O'Dowd prominently in the foreground, with the four female stars appearing in the background and coloured with a blue wash. The decision was described as both sexist and racist, with O'Dowd describing the decision as \"ill-judged, insensitive and everything the film wasn't\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BigBoyler/status/363093898320556032 |title=chris o'dowd on Twitter: \"@billwhatonair it's ridiculous, it's misleading, it's ill-judged, insensitive and everything the film wasn't.\" |publisher=Twitter |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | date = 6 August 2013 | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-23586169 | work = [[BBC News]] | title = Sapphires DVD complaint over O'Dowd image prompts apology }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Douglas |first= Tim. | date = 2 August 2013 | url = http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/film/the-sapphires-us-dvd-cover-vile-says-chris-odowd/story-e6frg8pf-1226690262756 | title = The Sapphires US DVD cover 'vile', says Chris O'Dowd | work = [[The Australian]] | accessdate = 3 August 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Lu | first = Ann | date = 3 August 2013 | url = http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/496465/20130803/sapphires-dvd-cover-art-racist-sexist-deborah.htm | title = U.S. DVD Cover Of Aussie Film 'The Sapphires' Called 'Sexist' And 'Racist' | work = [[International Business Times]] | accessdate = 3 August 2013 }}</ref>\nAnchor Bay expressed regret for any \"unintentional upset caused\" and said different artwork was being considered for future orders.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/05/the-sapphires-dvd-racist_n_3709074.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Mallika | last=Rao | title=Is This DVD Cover Racist? | date=5 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\nIn Australia, the film was the highest-earning Australian film on its opening weekend, grossing $2,320,000 from 275 cinemas.<ref name=\"smh\" /> [[News.com.au]] said it was the strongest first weekend for an Australian-made film since ''[[Tomorrow, When the War Began (film)|Tomorrow, When the War Began]]'', which earned $3,860,000 upon its 2010 release.<ref name=\"newscomau\">{{cite news | title=The Sapphires a box office smash hit on opening weekend |date=13 August 2012 | work=[[News.com.au]] |publisher=[[News Limited]] (News Corporation) | url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/movies/the-sapphires-a-box-office-smash-hit-on-opening-weekend/story-e6frfmvr-1226449423305 |first=Neala |last=Johnson | accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref> As of 31 October 2012, the film had grossed AU$14,215,596 at the Australian box office.<ref name=\"urbancinefile.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.urbancinefile.com.au/home/boxoffice.asp |title=Box Office |publisher=Urban Cinefile |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref>\n\nThe film was far less successful in international markets than in its Australian release, with roughly $5 million from all international releases combined versus over $14 million in its Australian release alone.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=sapphires.htm | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | publisher= Amazon.com|title=The Sapphires (2013) - International Box Office Results}}</ref>\n\nIn France, the film opened at #13 with just 35,786 admissions from 162 screens over its first week (25,847 over five days).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allocine.fr/boxoffice/boxofficedetail_gen_pays=5001.html?date=2012-08-08 |title=Box Office Cin\u00e9ma France - AlloCin\u00e9 |website=Allocine.fr |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> It was dubbed \"Le Flop\" by French box office website Le Box Office Pour Les Nuls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leboxofficepourlesnuls.com/2012/08/14/lundi-13-aout-2012-les-chiffres-cles-du-box-office/ |title=LUNDI 13 AOUT 2012 : LES CHIFFRES CLES DU BOX-OFFICE |publisher=Le box-office pour les nuls |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> In its first major English-language opening outside of Australia, the UK, the film opened at #7 and to a little under 25% of the box office it earned in its Australian opening weekend, on a roughly similar number of screens (279 vs. 233). The film exited UK cinemas after just 5 weeks in release with a final box office take of \u00a3680,643, equivalent to around AU$1m. The UK final box office takings were less than 1/14 of the film's Australian final box office takings.<ref name=\"mojo-uk\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/intl/uk/?yr=2012&wk=49&p.htm|title=United Kingdom Box Office|date=2012-12-19|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> In its United States release, where the film only appeared in the top 20 for one weekend (at #19, 5\u20137 April 2013), the film completed its run with just under $2.5m, and releases in Germany and the Netherlands yielded under $100,000 each.<ref name=\"mojo-intl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=sapphires.htm |accessdate=20 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513111758/http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=sapphires.htm |title=The Sapphires|archivedate=13 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n<!-- critical overview -->\n''The Sapphires'' received positive reviews from Cannes, dubbed as the Australian version of ''[[Dreamgirls (film)|Dreamgirls]]'' (2006), another film based on a play about a '60s girl group.<ref>{{cite news | title=Cannes unveils an unexpected gem (+trailer) |date=24 May 2012 | work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |publisher=[[APN News & Media]] | url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=10807651 |first=Kerry |last=O'Shea | accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Chris O'Dowd's 'The Sapphires' receives rave reviews at Cannes Film Festival \u2013 VIDEO|date=21 May 2012 | work=IrishCentral |publisher= | url= http://www.irishcentral.com/ent/Chris-ODowds-The-Sapphires-receives-rave-reviews-at-Cannes-Film-Festival-152268075.html |first=Jake |last=Coyle | accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a score of 91% based on reviews from 131 critics; their average rating was calculated as 6.9/10.<ref name=\"RottenTomatoes\">{{cite web|url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_sapphires_2012/|title = The Sapphires Movie Reviews, Pictures|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=5 October 2012}}</ref> Metacritic gives the film a \"generally positive\" rating of 67% based on reviews from 30 critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-sapphires |title=The Sapphires Reviews |website=Metacritic |date=2013-03-19 |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref>\n\n<!-- International critics -->\nGuy Lodge from ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' said [[Chris O'Dowd]]'s \"dorky-dirty warmth and manic performance energy... keeps the proceedings bouncy even when the script loses its own fizz.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Guy Lodge |url= http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117947584/ |title=Variety Reviews \u2013 The Sapphires |work=Variety |date=20 May 2012 |accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref> \nMark Adams of ''[[Screen International]]'' called O'Dowd an \"increasingly charismatic screen presence\" who \"helps give the film an edginess, spontaneity and some real laugh-out-loud moments.\"<ref>{{cite news | title=The Sapphires \u2013 Review |date=21 May 2012 | work=[[Screen International]] |publisher=[[EMAP|Emap International Limited]] | url= http://www.screendaily.com/reviews/the-latest/the-sapphires/5042342.article |first=Mark |last=Adams | accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref>\nEric Kohn from [[IndieWire]] gave it a C-, believing that it \"belongs on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] more than the big screen\".<ref>{{cite news |last =Kohn |first =Eric | title = CANNES REVIEW: Why Cannes Breakout 'The Sapphires' Belongs On Broadway More Than the Big Screen | work = [[IndieWire]] | date = 21 May 2012 | url = http://www.indiewire.com/article/cannes-review-why-cannes-breakout-the-sapphires-belongs-on-broadway-more-than-the-big-screen | accessdate =17 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\nHenry Barnes of ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave the film three stars out of five, calling it \"a sweet 'n' dumb feelgood bopper.\"<ref>{{cite news | title=Cannes 2012: The Sapphires \u2013 review |date=21 May 2012 | work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] | url= https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/may/21/the-sapphires-review?newsfeed=true |first=Henry |last=Barnes | accessdate=28 May 2012 | location=London}}</ref> \nBrad Brevet of ''Rope of Silicon'' gave it a B-, summing it up as, \"good music, good performances and good fun and should play well across several demographic quadrants.\"<ref>{{cite news |last =Brevet |first =Brad | title = 'The Sapphires' Movie Review \u2013 2012 Cannes Film Festival | work = Rope of Silicon | date = 21 May 2012 | url = http://www.ropeofsilicon.com/sapphires-movie-review-2012-cannes-film-festival/ | accessdate =28 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\n[[Robbie Collin]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' gave the \"workaday Australian comedy\" three stars, calling it \"uncomplicated\" but praising Chris O'Dowd for elevating every scene he is in.<ref>{{cite news | title=Cannes 2012: The Hunt/ Beyond The Hills / The Sapphires, review |date=21 May 2012 | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] | url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/cannes-film-festival/9279361/Cannes-2012-The-Hunt-Beyond-The-Hills-The-Sapphires-review.html |first=Robbie |last=Collin | accessdate=17 July 2012 | location=London}}</ref> \nRoss Miller of ''Thoughts On Film'' gave the film three stars, saying that it \"may not break any especially new ground or end up in a place you're not expecting but along the way it's a genuinely pleasant watch.\"<ref>{{cite news | title=Movie Review: The Sapphires |date=30 October 2012 | work=Thoughts On Film|publisher=Thoughts On Film| url= http://thoughtsonfilm.co.uk/movie-reviews/the-sapphires-movie-review/ |first=Ross |last=Miller | accessdate=2 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Australian critics -->\nFiona Williams of [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]] awarded the film three-and-a-half stars out of five, commenting that \"There's much to love, lots to like... and enough roof-lifting musical numbers to make up for the dodgy bits.\"<ref>{{cite news | title=The Sapphires (review) |date=| work=[[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]] |publisher= | url= http://www.sbs.com.au/films/movie/13488/the-sapphires |first=Fiona |last=Williams | accessdate=28 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nAcademic Bruno Starrs makes the argument that the film's Aboriginal protagonists undergo a journey in which they learn the importance of choosing the protest songs of black Soul over the white coloniser's \"whining\" Country and Western songs. Their song choices are an assertion of Indigenous sovereignty and Starrs argues that the Aboriginal Australian 'Welcome to Country' is twice subverted to reinforce this theme, firstly in the Cummeragunja pub and secondly in war-torn Vietnam.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eprints.qut.edu.au/75050/ |title=Sovereignty, song and 'The Sapphires' (Wayne Blair 2012) &#124; QUT ePrints |website=Eprints.qut.edu.au |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{Anchor|Accolades|Awards}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Ceremony\n! Category\n! Recipient\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[AWGIE Awards|45th AWGIE Awards]]<ref>{{cite news | title=The Sapphires and Not Suitable For Children top AWGIE Awards |date=27 August 2012 | work=Inside Film |publisher= | url=http://if.com.au/2012/08/27/article/The-Sapphires-and-Not-Suitable-For-Children-top-AWGIE-Awards/APOYDDBIPU.html |first=Anthony |last=Soegito | accessdate=17 July 2012}}</ref>\n| Best Feature Film (screenplay) \u2013 Adaptation\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Keith Thompson<br>[[Tony Briggs]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|[[Major AWGIE Award|Most Outstanding Script of 2012]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[ARIA Music Awards of 2012|26th ARIA Music Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history/year/2012|title=2012 ARIA Awards Winners By Year |publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) |accessdate=7 October 2012 }}</ref>\n| [[ARIA Award for Best Original Soundtrack, Cast or Show Album|Best Original Soundtrack/Cast/Show Album]]\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Chicago International Film Festival|48th Chicago International Film Festival]]\n| Gold Hugo for Best Feature\n|rowspan=2|[[Wayne Blair]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Denver Film Festival|35th Denver Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Cangialosi|first=Jason|title=35th Starz Denver Film Festival Award Winners|url=http://www.milehighcinema.com/2012/11/15/35th-starz-denver-film-festival-award-winners/|publisher=Mile High Cinema|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref>\n| People's Choice Award for Best Narrative Feature\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"17\" | [[AACTA Awards]]<ref>{{cite news | title=The Sapphires top of the AACTAs with 12 nominations |date=3 December 2012 | work=[[Herald Sun]] |publisher=[[The Herald and Weekly Times]] (News Corporation) | url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/aacta-award-nominations/story-e6frf96f-1226529040189 |first1=Vicky |last1=Roach|first2=Holly |last2=Byrnes | accessdate=8 December 2012}}</ref><br><small>([[2nd AACTA Awards|2nd]])</small>\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n| [[Rosemary Blight]], Kylie du Fresne\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]\n| Wayne Blair\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[AACTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n| Keith Thompson\n|{{won}}\n|-\n| Tony Briggs\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Lead Actor]]\n| [[Chris O'Dowd]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Lead Actress]]\n| [[Deborah Mailman]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| [[Jessica Mauboy]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| [[Warwick Thornton]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n| [[Dany Cooper]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=5|[[AACTA Award for Best Sound|Best Sound]]\n| Andrew Plain\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Bry Jones\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Pete Smith\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Ben Osmo\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| John Simpson\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]]\n| Melinda Doring\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]]\n| Tess Schofield\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]]\n| James Rogers\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Deadly Awards 2013]]<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-09-11/abc-among-those-honoured-in-2013-deadly-awards/4949856 Aboriginal magistrate Pat O'Shane, Archie Roach honoured at Deadly Awards], ''ABC News'', 11 September 2013.</ref>\n|colspan=2|Film of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb title|1673697|The Sapphires}}\n* {{mojo title|sapphires|The Sapphires}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|the_sapphires_2012|The Sapphires}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-sapphires|The Sapphires}}\n\n{{AACTA Award Best Film 2010\u20132029}}\n{{Films and television series about Indigenous Australia |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sapphires, The}}\n[[Category:2012 films]]\n[[Category:2010